{"title_page": "Bonginkosi Madikizela", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix     = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                 = Bonginkosi Madikizela\n| native_name          = \n| native_name_lang     = \n| honorific-suffix     = [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Western Cape)|MPP]]\n| image                = Bonginkosi Madikizela DA Rally (cropped).jpg\n| image_size           = 220px\n| smallimage           = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                  = \n| caption              = \n| office               = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Transport and Public Works]]\n| premier              = [[Alan Winde]]\n| term_start           = 23 May 2019\n| term_end             = \n| predecessor          = [[Donald Grant (politician)|Donald Grant]]\n| successor            = \n| office1              = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Human Settlements]]\n| premier1             = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start1          = 26 May 2014\n| term_end1            = 22 May 2019\n| predecessor1         = Position established\n| successor1           = [[Tertuis Simmers]]\n| office2              = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Housing]]\n| premier2             = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start2          = 7 May 2009\n| term_end2            = 26 May 2014\n| predecessor2         = Whitey Jacobs\n| successor2           = Position reconfigured\n| office3              =[[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Provincial Leader of the Western Cape Democratic Alliance]]  \n| deputy3              = [[Albert Fritz]]\n| term_start3          = 7 October 2017<br/>{{small|Interim: 1 February 2017 - 7 October 2017}}\n| term_end3            = \n| predecessor3         = [[Patricia de Lille]]\n| successor3           = \n| office4              = [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Deputy Provincial Leader of the Western Cape Democratic Alliance]] \n| leader4              = [[Patricia de Lille]]\n| term_start4          = 18 April 2015\n| term_end4            = 7 October 2017\n| predecessor4         = [[Theuns Botha]]\n| successor4           = [[Albert Fritz]]\n| office5              =[[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n| term_start5          = 6 May 2009\n|constituency5         = \n| birthname            = \n| birth_date           = {{birth date and age|1975|3|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place          = \n| death_date           =  \n| death_place          = \n| citizenship          =\n| nationality          = [[South Africa]]n\n| party                = [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]]\n| otherparty           = [[United Democratic Movement]]<br/>[[African National Congress]]\n| spouse               = \n| partner              =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| children             = \n| residence            = \n| relations            = [[Winnie Madikizela-Mandela]] (aunt)\n| education            =\n| alma_mater           = \n| occupation           = \n| profession           = [[Politician]]\n| known_for            = \n| committees           = \n| portfolio            = \n| awards               =  <!-- For civilian awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |mawards= is not set -->\n| website              = \n}}\n'''Bonginkosi Success Madikizela''' (born 15 March 1975) is a South African [[politician]].\n\nBorn in the former [[Cape Province]], now the [[Eastern Cape]], Madikizela soon moved to [[Khayelitsha]] and became politically active in the area. He was previously a member of the [[African National Congress]] (ANC) and [[United Democratic Movement]] (UDM), prior to him joining the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (DA) in 2008. He was elected a [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]] for the DA in 2009. Premier [[Helen Zille]] appointed him as the Provincial Minister for Housing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mg.co.za/article/2009-05-08-return-of-the-white-men |title=Return of the White Men |date=8 May 2009 |publisher=Mail & Guardian|accessdate=8 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westerncape.gov.za/eng/pubs/news/2009/may/180702 |title=Appointment of the Western Cape Provincial Cabinet |date=8 May 2009 |work=Cape Gateway |publisher=Provincial Government of the Western Cape |accessdate=8 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, he was named Provincial Minister of Human Settlements. A year later, in 2015, Madikizela unseated party stalwart [[Theuns Botha]] as deputy provincial leader of the DA. DA Provincial leader [[Patricia de Lille]] resigned in February 2017 and left Madikizela in charge as acting provincial leader. He won a full term in October 2017. In 2019, Madikizela became the Provincial Minister of Transport and Public Works.\n==Early life==\nMadikizela was born in the then [[Cape Province]] on 15 March 1975. His aunt was prominent anti-apartheid activist [[Winnie Madikizela Mandela]]. He has a Bachelor of Commerce Degree in Human Resource Management and a certificate in Information Technology.\n==Political career==\n[[File:MEC Madikizela (2).jpg|thumb|left|Madikizela speaking at a DA rally prior to the 2011 municipal elections]]\nMadikizela had previously been an active member of the ANC. He became prominent in 2005, when he led a group of disaffected ANC members in the Makhaza area of [[Khayelitsha]] who had been supportive of former [[Western Cape]] Premier and ANC Provincial Chairperson [[Ebrahim Rasool]] in his leadership battle with [[Mcebisi Skwatsha]].<ref>[https://mg.co.za/article/2009-09-26-being-black-in-the-da Being black in the DA]. Retrieved on 24 July 2019.</ref>\n\nAfter Skwatsha won the leadership election, Madikizela and some of Rasool's supporters in [[Khayelitsha]] claimed that they were being marginalised, and later excluded as possible ANC candidates for the local government elections in 2006. In early 2006, Madikizela along with several other ANC members, including some party councillors, were expelled from the party after it became known of their intention to contest the local government elections as independent candidates.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mtyala|first=Quinton|title=Dissidents challenge ANC in local elections|url=http://152.111.1.87/argief/berigte/citypress/2006/01/15/C1/2/02.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130410010728/http://152.111.1.87/argief/berigte/citypress/2006/01/15/C1/2/02.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 April 2013|work=City Press|publisher=City Press|accessdate=25 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mariane|first=Merten|title=Crackdown on ANC poll rebels|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2006-01-27-crackdown-on-anc-poll-rebels|work=Mail and Guardian|publisher=Mail and Guardian|accessdate=25 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nAlthough he was not elected as a councillor, Madikizela remained politically active, joining the [[United Democratic Movement]] (UDM) in 2007. He was appointed the party's Cape Town Metro Regional Secretary until a party investigation found that he had secretly convinced party members to join the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Hartley|first=Aziz|title=Madikizela recruited for the DA - UDM|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/madikizela-recruited-for-the-da-udm-1.416548#.UVGwSzfkeHg|work=Cape Times|publisher=INLSA|accessdate=26 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe was subsequently hired as a communication officer at the [[City of Cape Town]], and later a spokesperson in the office of former Mayor of Cape Town, [[Helen Zille]].\n\nHe officially became a member of DA in October 2008. Following the [[2009 South African general election|April 2009 general election]], newly-elected Premier [[Helen Zille]] appointed him to the post of Provincial Minister of Housing. He was appointed as Provincial Minister of Human Settlements following his re-election in May 2014.<ref>[https://mg.co.za/article/2009-05-08-zille-appoints-western-cape-cabinet Zille appoints Western Cape Cabinet]. Retrieved on 24 July 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/premier-zilles-new-cape-cabinet-1691800 Premier Zille\u2019s new Cape cabinet]. Retrieved on 24 July 2019.</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Madikizela was elected deputy provincial leader of the Democratic Alliance in the Western Cape, unseating DA veteran [[Theuns Botha]].<ref>{{cite news |title=De Lille crowned new Western Cape DA leader |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2015-04-18-de-lille-crowned-new-western-cape-da-leader/ |accessdate=19 March 2020 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=18 April 2015}}</ref> He was subsequently named the acting provincial leader in February 2017, when incumbent [[Patricia de Lille]] resigned. He was elected to the position for a full term on 7 October 2017.<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/capetimes/news/de-lille-resigns-as-da-provincial-leader-2097385 De Lille resigns as DA provincial leader]. Retrieved on 24 July 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.enca.com/south-africa/bonginkosi-madikizela-elected-da-western-cape-interim-leader Bonginkosi Madikizela elected DA Western Cape acting leader]. Retrieved on 24 July 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/wccongress-madikizela-elected-as-das-provincial-leader-11514383 #WCcongress: Madikizela elected as DA\u2019s provincial leader]. Retrieved on 24 July 2019.</ref>\n\nNewly elected Premier [[Alan Winde]] appointed Madikizela as Provincial Minister of Transport and Public Works in May 2019. Madikizela is also the Leader of Government Business in the Provincial Parliament.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-23-western-cape-premier-alan-windes-cabinet-a-mix-of-old-and-new/ Western Cape premier Alan Winde's cabinet a mix of old and new]. Retrieved on 23 May 2019.</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, he declared his intention to run for interim Federal Leader of the DA following [[Mmusi Maimane]]'s resignation.<ref>Mailovich, Claudi. [https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-10-31-da-leadership-race-to-replace-mmusi-maimane-is-in-full-swing/ DA leadership race to replace Mmusi Maimane is in full swing], ''BusinessLIVE'', 31 October 2019. Retrieved on 8 November 2019.</ref> Madikizela dropped out of the leadership race on 11 November 2019.<ref>Tandwa, Lizeka, Madia, Tshidi. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/bonginkosi-madikizela-pulls-out-of-da-leadership-race-20191111 Bonginkosi Madikizela pulls out of DA leadership race], ''News24'', 11 November 2019. Retrieved on 11 November 2019.</ref> [[John Steenhuisen]] was elected interim leader on 17 November 2019.\n\nOn 26 January 2020, Madikizela announced that he would consider running for DA Federal Leader at the [[2020 Democratic Alliance Federal Congress|party's Federal Congress]] in May.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Charles |first1=Marvin |title=Bonginkosi Madikizela says he will be running for DA leader role |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/bonginkosi-madikizela-says-he-will-be-running-for-da-leader-role-41421965 |accessdate=26 January 2020 |newspaper=IOL |date=26 January 2020 |location=Cape Town}}</ref> He declined to run for the post on 10 February 2020. He will, however, run for re-election at the party's provincial conference later on in the year.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Makinana |first1=Andisiwe |title=Western Cape DA leader Bonginkosi Madikizela will not stand for federal leadership position |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2020-02-10-western-cape-da-leader-bonginkosi-madikizela-will-not-stand-for-federal-leadership-position/ |accessdate=10 February 2020 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn September 2010, the ANC called for his resignation after his answer to a parliamentary question from the ANC's Pierre Uys over the provision of housing in the Western Cape. Madikizela had said \"unfortunately\" there was no [[influx control]] to regulate the movement of people into the Western Cape. The ANC called for Helen Zille to fire him, angered that he had linked the provision of services to the apartheid policy of influx control.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mtyala|first=Quinton|title='People Must Come before Houses'|url=https://www.questia.com/library/1G1-236321722/people-must-come-before-houses|work=Cape Times|publisher=INLSA|accessdate=26 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Mandela Park===\nMadikizela has been embroiled in a number of controversies surrounding housing developments in [[Mandela Park, Khayelitsha]].  He has been accused by the [[Mandela Park Backyarders]] as well as journalists of breaking a promise of giving residents of the community houses in new Mandela Park developments.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abahlali.org/node/5739 |title=Sowetan: MEC under siege over \u2018false promise\u2019 |date=23 Sep 2009 |publisher=Abahlali baseMjondolo}}</ref>  The controversy has resulted in large demonstrations and blockades against construction in the community.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://antieviction.org.za/2009/11/12/hundreds-protested-yesterday-in-mandela-park-after-assault-by-chippa-security-guards-demostrations-to-continue/ |title=Hundreds Protested Yesterday |date=12 Nov 2009 |publisher=Anti-Eviction Campaign |access-date=2010-10-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101009232142/http://antieviction.org.za/2009/11/12/hundreds-protested-yesterday-in-mandela-park-after-assault-by-chippa-security-guards-demostrations-to-continue/# |archive-date=2010-10-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pambazuka.org/en/category/socialmovements/66813 |title=Construction suspended, still no official response |date=9 Sep 2010 |publisher=Pambazuka News}}</ref> The community of Mandela Park has also accused the MEC of refusing to meet with them.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://westcapenews.com/?p=2138 |title=Claims of illegal RDP sales in Mandela Park |date=7 Oct 2010 |publisher=WestCapeNews}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Democratic Alliance (South Africa)}}\n{{Winde provincial cabinet}}\n{{Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament}}\n{{Zille provincial cabinet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Madikizela, Bonginkosi}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Democratic Alliance (South Africa) politicians]]\n[[Category:People from the Western Cape]]\n[[Category:United Democratic Movement (South Africa) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix     = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                 = Bonginkosi Madikizela\n| native_name          = \n| native_name_lang     = \n| honorific-suffix     = [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Western Cape)|MPP]]\n| image                = Bonginkosi Madikizela DA Rally (cropped).jpg\n| image_size           = 220px\n| smallimage           = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                  = \n| caption              = \n| office               = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Transport and Public Works]]\n| premier              = [[Alan Winde]]\n| term_start           = 23 May 2019\n| term_end             = \n| predecessor          = [[Donald Grant (politician)|Donald Grant]]\n| successor            = \n| office1              = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Human Settlements]]\n| premier1             = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start1          = 26 May 2014\n| term_end1            = 22 May 2019\n| predecessor1         = Position established\n| successor1           = [[Tertuis Simmers]]\n| office2              = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Housing]]\n| premier2             = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start2          = 7 May 2009\n| term_end2            = 26 May 2014\n| predecessor2         = Whitey Jacobs\n| successor2           = Position reconfigured\n| office3              =[[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Provincial Leader of the Western Cape Democratic Alliance]]  \n| deputy3              = [[Albert Fritz]]\n| term_start3          = 7 October 2017<br/>{{small|Interim: 1 February 2017 - 7 October 2017}}\n| term_end3            = \n| predecessor3         = [[Patricia de Lille]]\n| successor3           = \n| office4              = [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Deputy Provincial Leader of the Western Cape Democratic Alliance]] \n| leader4              = [[Patricia de Lille]]\n| term_start4          = 18 April 2015\n| term_end4            = 7 October 2017\n| predecessor4         = [[Theuns Botha]]\n| successor4           = [[Albert Fritz]]\n| office5              =[[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n| term_start5          = 6 May 2009\n|constituency5         = \n| birthname            = \n| birth_date           = {{birth date and age|1975|3|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place          = \n| death_date           =  \n| death_place          = \n| citizenship          =\n| nationality          = [[South Africa]]n\n| party                = [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]]\n| otherparty           = [[United Democratic Movement]]<br/>[[African National Congress]]\n| spouse               = \n| partner              =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| children             = \n| residence            = \n| relations            = [[Winnie Madikizela-Mandela]] (aunt)\n| education            =\n| alma_mater           = \n| occupation           = \n| profession           = [[Politician]]\n| known_for            = \n| committees           = \n| portfolio            = \n| awards               =  <!-- For civilian awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |mawards= is not set -->\n| website              = \n}}\n'''Bonginkosi Success Madikizela''' (born 15 March 1975) is a South African [[politician]].\n\nBorn in the [[Eastern Cape]] region of then [[Cape Province]], Madikizela soon moved to [[Khayelitsha]] and became politically active in the area. He was previously a member of the [[African National Congress]] (ANC) and [[United Democratic Movement]] (UDM), prior to him joining the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (DA) in 2008. He was elected a [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]] for the DA in 2009. Premier [[Helen Zille]] appointed him as the Provincial Minister for Housing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mg.co.za/article/2009-05-08-return-of-the-white-men |title=Return of the White Men |date=8 May 2009 |publisher=Mail & Guardian|accessdate=8 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westerncape.gov.za/eng/pubs/news/2009/may/180702 |title=Appointment of the Western Cape Provincial Cabinet |date=8 May 2009 |work=Cape Gateway |publisher=Provincial Government of the Western Cape |accessdate=8 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, he was named Provincial Minister of Human Settlements. A year later, in 2015, Madikizela unseated party stalwart [[Theuns Botha]] as deputy provincial leader of the DA. DA Provincial leader [[Patricia de Lille]] resigned in February 2017 and left Madikizela in charge as acting provincial leader. He won a full term in October 2017. In 2019, Madikizela became the Provincial Minister of Transport and Public Works.\n==Early life==\nMadikizela was born in the then [[Cape Province]] on 15 March 1975. His aunt was prominent anti-apartheid activist [[Winnie Madikizela Mandela]]. He has a Bachelor of Commerce Degree in Human Resource Management and a certificate in Information Technology.\n==Political career==\n[[File:MEC Madikizela (2).jpg|thumb|left|Madikizela speaking at a DA rally prior to the 2011 municipal elections]]\nMadikizela had previously been an active member of the ANC. He became prominent in 2005, when he led a group of disaffected ANC members in the Makhaza area of [[Khayelitsha]] who had been supportive of former [[Western Cape]] Premier and ANC Provincial Chairperson [[Ebrahim Rasool]] in his leadership battle with [[Mcebisi Skwatsha]].<ref>[https://mg.co.za/article/2009-09-26-being-black-in-the-da Being black in the DA]. Retrieved on 24 July 2019.</ref>\n\nAfter Skwatsha won the leadership election, Madikizela and some of Rasool's supporters in [[Khayelitsha]] claimed that they were being marginalised, and later excluded as possible ANC candidates for the local government elections in 2006. In early 2006, Madikizela along with several other ANC members, including some party councillors, were expelled from the party after it became known of their intention to contest the local government elections as independent candidates.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mtyala|first=Quinton|title=Dissidents challenge ANC in local elections|url=http://152.111.1.87/argief/berigte/citypress/2006/01/15/C1/2/02.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130410010728/http://152.111.1.87/argief/berigte/citypress/2006/01/15/C1/2/02.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 April 2013|work=City Press|publisher=City Press|accessdate=25 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mariane|first=Merten|title=Crackdown on ANC poll rebels|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2006-01-27-crackdown-on-anc-poll-rebels|work=Mail and Guardian|publisher=Mail and Guardian|accessdate=25 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nAlthough he was not elected as a councillor, Madikizela remained politically active, joining the [[United Democratic Movement]] (UDM) in 2007. He was appointed the party's Cape Town Metro Regional Secretary until a party investigation found that he had secretly convinced party members to join the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Hartley|first=Aziz|title=Madikizela recruited for the DA - UDM|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/madikizela-recruited-for-the-da-udm-1.416548#.UVGwSzfkeHg|work=Cape Times|publisher=INLSA|accessdate=26 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe was subsequently hired as a communication officer at the [[City of Cape Town]], and later a spokesperson in the office of former Mayor of Cape Town, [[Helen Zille]].\n\nHe officially became a member of DA in October 2008. Following the [[2009 South African general election|April 2009 general election]], newly-elected Premier [[Helen Zille]] appointed him to the post of Provincial Minister of Housing. He was appointed as Provincial Minister of Human Settlements following his re-election in May 2014.<ref>[https://mg.co.za/article/2009-05-08-zille-appoints-western-cape-cabinet Zille appoints Western Cape Cabinet]. Retrieved on 24 July 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/premier-zilles-new-cape-cabinet-1691800 Premier Zille\u2019s new Cape cabinet]. Retrieved on 24 July 2019.</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Madikizela was elected deputy provincial leader of the Democratic Alliance in the Western Cape, unseating DA veteran [[Theuns Botha]].<ref>{{cite news |title=De Lille crowned new Western Cape DA leader |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2015-04-18-de-lille-crowned-new-western-cape-da-leader/ |accessdate=19 March 2020 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=18 April 2015}}</ref> He was subsequently named the acting provincial leader in February 2017, when incumbent [[Patricia de Lille]] resigned. He was elected to the position for a full term on 7 October 2017.<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/capetimes/news/de-lille-resigns-as-da-provincial-leader-2097385 De Lille resigns as DA provincial leader]. Retrieved on 24 July 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.enca.com/south-africa/bonginkosi-madikizela-elected-da-western-cape-interim-leader Bonginkosi Madikizela elected DA Western Cape acting leader]. Retrieved on 24 July 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/wccongress-madikizela-elected-as-das-provincial-leader-11514383 #WCcongress: Madikizela elected as DA\u2019s provincial leader]. Retrieved on 24 July 2019.</ref>\n\nNewly elected Premier [[Alan Winde]] appointed Madikizela as Provincial Minister of Transport and Public Works in May 2019. Madikizela is also the Leader of Government Business in the Provincial Parliament.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-23-western-cape-premier-alan-windes-cabinet-a-mix-of-old-and-new/ Western Cape premier Alan Winde's cabinet a mix of old and new]. Retrieved on 23 May 2019.</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, he declared his intention to run for interim Federal Leader of the DA following [[Mmusi Maimane]]'s resignation.<ref>Mailovich, Claudi. [https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-10-31-da-leadership-race-to-replace-mmusi-maimane-is-in-full-swing/ DA leadership race to replace Mmusi Maimane is in full swing], ''BusinessLIVE'', 31 October 2019. Retrieved on 8 November 2019.</ref> Madikizela dropped out of the leadership race on 11 November 2019.<ref>Tandwa, Lizeka, Madia, Tshidi. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/bonginkosi-madikizela-pulls-out-of-da-leadership-race-20191111 Bonginkosi Madikizela pulls out of DA leadership race], ''News24'', 11 November 2019. Retrieved on 11 November 2019.</ref> [[John Steenhuisen]] was elected interim leader on 17 November 2019.\n\nOn 26 January 2020, Madikizela announced that he would consider running for DA Federal Leader at the [[2020 Democratic Alliance Federal Congress|party's Federal Congress]] in May.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Charles |first1=Marvin |title=Bonginkosi Madikizela says he will be running for DA leader role |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/bonginkosi-madikizela-says-he-will-be-running-for-da-leader-role-41421965 |accessdate=26 January 2020 |newspaper=IOL |date=26 January 2020 |location=Cape Town}}</ref> He declined to run for the post on 10 February 2020. He will, however, run for re-election at the party's provincial conference later on in the year.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Makinana |first1=Andisiwe |title=Western Cape DA leader Bonginkosi Madikizela will not stand for federal leadership position |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2020-02-10-western-cape-da-leader-bonginkosi-madikizela-will-not-stand-for-federal-leadership-position/ |accessdate=10 February 2020 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn September 2010, the ANC called for his resignation after his answer to a parliamentary question from the ANC's Pierre Uys over the provision of housing in the Western Cape. Madikizela had said \"unfortunately\" there was no [[influx control]] to regulate the movement of people into the Western Cape. The ANC called for Helen Zille to fire him, angered that he had linked the provision of services to the apartheid policy of influx control.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mtyala|first=Quinton|title='People Must Come before Houses'|url=https://www.questia.com/library/1G1-236321722/people-must-come-before-houses|work=Cape Times|publisher=INLSA|accessdate=26 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Mandela Park===\nMadikizela has been embroiled in a number of controversies surrounding housing developments in [[Mandela Park, Khayelitsha]].  He has been accused by the [[Mandela Park Backyarders]] as well as journalists of breaking a promise of giving residents of the community houses in new Mandela Park developments.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abahlali.org/node/5739 |title=Sowetan: MEC under siege over \u2018false promise\u2019 |date=23 Sep 2009 |publisher=Abahlali baseMjondolo}}</ref>  The controversy has resulted in large demonstrations and blockades against construction in the community.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://antieviction.org.za/2009/11/12/hundreds-protested-yesterday-in-mandela-park-after-assault-by-chippa-security-guards-demostrations-to-continue/ |title=Hundreds Protested Yesterday |date=12 Nov 2009 |publisher=Anti-Eviction Campaign |access-date=2010-10-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101009232142/http://antieviction.org.za/2009/11/12/hundreds-protested-yesterday-in-mandela-park-after-assault-by-chippa-security-guards-demostrations-to-continue/# |archive-date=2010-10-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pambazuka.org/en/category/socialmovements/66813 |title=Construction suspended, still no official response |date=9 Sep 2010 |publisher=Pambazuka News}}</ref> The community of Mandela Park has also accused the MEC of refusing to meet with them.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://westcapenews.com/?p=2138 |title=Claims of illegal RDP sales in Mandela Park |date=7 Oct 2010 |publisher=WestCapeNews}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Democratic Alliance (South Africa)}}\n{{Winde provincial cabinet}}\n{{Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament}}\n{{Zille provincial cabinet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Madikizela, Bonginkosi}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Democratic Alliance (South Africa) politicians]]\n[[Category:People from the Western Cape]]\n[[Category:United Democratic Movement (South Africa) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n", "name_user": "Lefcentreright", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bonginkosi_Madikizela"}
{"title_page": "Consort Yu", "text_new": "{{Chinese name|[[Yu (Chinese name)|Yu]]}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Consort Yu<br>\u865e\u59ec\n| image = Consort Yu.jpg\n| image_size = 180px\n| alt =\n| caption = A portrait of Consort Yu from ''Baimei Xinyong Tuzhuan'' (\u767e\u7f8e\u65b0\u8a60\u5716\u50b3) by Yan Xiyuan\n| birth_date = Unknown\n| birth_place = [[Jiangsu]]\n| death_date = 202 BC\n| death_place = [[Lingbi County]], [[Anhui]]\n| other_names = \"Yu the Beauty\" (\u865e\u7f8e\u4eba)\n| spouse = [[Xiang Yu]]\n| relations = Yu Ziqi (brother)\n}}\n'''Consort Yu''' (died 202 BC), also known as \"Yu the Beauty\", was the concubine of the warlord [[Xiang Yu]], who competed with [[Emperor Gaozu of Han|Liu Bang (Emperor Gao)]], the founder of the [[Han dynasty]], for supremacy over China in the [[Chu\u2013Han Contention]] (206\u2013202 BC).\n\n==Life==\nConsort Yu's birth date is unknown and there are two accounts of her origin. The first said she was from Yanji Town (\u984f\u96c6\u9547) in [[Shuyang County]], while the other claimed that she was from [[Suzhou]], but both pointed that she was born in present-day [[Jiangsu]].\n\nIn 209 BC, Xiang Yu and his uncle [[Xiang Liang]] started a revolution to overthrow the [[Qin dynasty]]. Consort Yu's elder brother, Yu Ziqi (\u865e\u5b50\u671f), was serving in Xiang Liang's army as a general then. Consort Yu met Xiang Yu, fell in love with him and became his concubine. Since then, she had been following Xiang Yu on his military campaigns and refused to remain behind. She accompanied him on all battles.<ref>The China Journal - Volume 3, Issue 2 - Page 374 Arthur de Carle Sowerby - 1925</ref>\n\nIn 202 BC, Xiang Yu was besieged in the [[Battle of Gaixia]] by the combined forces of [[Emperor Gaozu of Han|Liu Bang]] (King of [[Han dynasty|Han]]), [[Han Xin]] and [[Peng Yue]]. The Han army started to sing folk songs from Xiang Yu's native land of [[Chu (state)|Chu]] to create a false impression that they had captured Chu. The morale of Xiang Yu's troops plummeted and several soldiers deserted. In despair, Xiang Yu indulged in alcohol and sang the ''[[Xiang Yu#Song of Gaixia|Song of Gaixia]]'' to express his sorrow. Consort Yu performed a [[sword dance]] and sang a verse in return. To prevent Xiang Yu from being distracted by his love for her, Consort Yu committed suicide with Xiang Yu's sword after singing. She was buried at Gaixia.\n\nA \"Consort Yu Tomb\" stands in present-day [[Lingbi County]], [[Anhui]].\n\n==Song of Consort Yu==\nThis verse was sung by Consort Yu after Xiang Yu sang the ''[[Xiang Yu#Song of Gaixia|Song of Gaixia]]''. She committed suicide with Xiang Yu's sword after singing.\n\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellmargin=\"0\"\n|-----\n| style=\"font-size:100%\" |\n\u6f22\u5175\u5df2\u7565\u5730\uff0c\n|\n''The Han army has conquered our land;''\n|-----\n| style=\"font-size:100%\" |\n\u56db\u9762\u695a\u6b4c\u8072\u3002\n|\n''Surrounded with the singing of Chu;''\n|-----\n| style=\"font-size:100%\" |\n\u5927\u738b\u7fa9\u6c23\u76e1\uff0c\n|\n''My lord's spirits are low;''\n|-----\n| style=\"font-size:100%\" |\n\u8ce4\u59be\u4f55\u804a\u751f\u3002\n|\n''Why then should I live?''\n|}\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe romance of Xiang Yu and Consort Yu has been the subject of plays, films and television series, even though not much about Consort Yu was recorded in history. The story was reenacted on stage in the [[Peking opera]] ''[[The Hegemon-King Bids His Concubine Farewell]]''. Poets such as [[Su Shi]], He Pu and [[Yuan Mei]] have written poems about Consort Yu as well. Actresses such as [[Idy Chan]], [[Melissa Ng]], [[Kristy Yang]], [[Rosamund Kwan]] and [[Liu Yifei]] have played the role of Consort Yu in films and television series.\n\nIn the video game ''[[Fate/Grand Order]]'', Consort Yu is an Assassin-class Servant voiced by [[Mariya Ise]]. Here, she is a vampire who survived to the present day under the alias Hinako Akuta and desires to reunite with Xiang Yu, who is unexpectedly a monstrous robotic Centaur programmed by [[Qin Shi Huang]] under code name [[Huiji District|Huiji]]-Yishi.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n* [[Sima Qian]]. ''[[Records of the Grand Historian]]'', Volume 7, Biography of Xiang Yu.\n\n{{People of the Chu\u2013Han contention}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yu, Consort}}\n[[Category:202 BC deaths]]\n[[Category:Women in ancient Chinese warfare]]\n[[Category:Chu\u2013Han contention people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:3rd-century BC women writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Chinese name|[[Yu (Chinese name)|Yu]]}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Consort Yu<br>\u865e\u59ec\n| image = Consort Yu.jpg\n| image_size = 180px\n| alt =\n| caption = A portrait of Consort Yu from ''Baimei Xinyong Tuzhuan'' (\u767e\u7f8e\u65b0\u8a60\u5716\u50b3) by Yan Xiyuan\n| birth_date = Unknown\n| birth_place = [[Jiangsu]]\n| death_date = 202 BC\n| death_place = [[Lingbi County]], [[Anhui]]\n| other_names = \"Yu the Beauty\" (\u865e\u7f8e\u4eba)\n| spouse = [[Xiang Yu]]\n| relations = Yu Ziqi (brother)\n}}\n'''Consort Yu''' (died 202 BC), also known as \"Yu the Beauty\", was the concubine of the warlord [[Xiang Yu]], who competed with [[Emperor Gaozu of Han|Liu Bang (Emperor Gao)]], the founder of the [[Han dynasty]], for supremacy over China in the [[Chu\u2013Han Contention]] (206\u2013202 BC).\n\n==Life==\nConsort Yu's birth date is unknown and there are two accounts of her origin. The first said she was from Yanji Town (\u984f\u96c6\u9547) in [[Shuyang County]], while the other claimed that she was from [[Suzhou]], but both pointed that she was born in present-day [[Jiangsu]].\n\nIn 209 BC, Xiang Yu and his uncle [[Xiang Liang]] started a revolution to overthrow the [[Qin dynasty]]. Consort Yu's elder brother, Yu Ziqi (\u865e\u5b50\u671f), was serving in Xiang Liang's army as a general then. Consort Yu met Xiang Yu, fell in love with him and became his concubine. Since then, she had been following Xiang Yu on his military campaigns and refused to remain behind. She accompanied him on all battles.<ref>The China Journal - Volume 3, Issue 2 - Page 374 Arthur de Carle Sowerby - 1925</ref>\n\nIn 202 BC, Xiang Yu was besieged in the [[Battle of Gaixia]] by the combined forces of [[Emperor Gaozu of Han|Liu Bang]] (King of [[Han dynasty|Han]]), [[Han Xin]] and [[Peng Yue]]. The Han army started to sing folk songs from Xiang Yu's native land of [[Chu (state)|Chu]] to create a false impression that they had captured Chu. The morale of Xiang Yu's troops plummeted and several soldiers deserted. In despair, Xiang Yu indulged in alcohol and sang the ''[[Xiang Yu#Song of Gaixia|Song of Gaixia]]'' to express his sorrow. Consort Yu performed a [[sword dance]] and sang a verse in return. To prevent Xiang Yu from being distracted by his love for her, Consort Yu committed suicide with Xiang Yu's sword after singing. She was buried at Gaixia.\n\nA \"Consort Yu Tomb\" stands in present-day [[Lingbi County]], [[Anhui]].\n\n==Song of Consort Yu==\nThis verse was sung by Consort Yu after Xiang Yu sang the ''[[Xiang Yu#Song of Gaixia|Song of Gaixia]]''. She committed suicide with Xiang Yu's sword after singing.\n\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellmargin=\"0\"\n|-----\n| style=\"font-size:100%\" |\n\u6f22\u5175\u5df2\u7565\u5730\uff0c\n|\n''The Han army has conquered our land;''\n|-----\n| style=\"font-size:100%\" |\n\u56db\u9762\u695a\u6b4c\u8072\u3002\n|\n''Surrounded with the singing of Chu;''\n|-----\n| style=\"font-size:100%\" |\n\u5927\u738b\u7fa9\u6c23\u76e1\uff0c\n|\n''My lord's spirits are low;''\n|-----\n| style=\"font-size:100%\" |\n\u8ce4\u59be\u4f55\u804a\u751f\u3002\n|\n''Why then should I live?''\n|}\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe romance of Xiang Yu and Consort Yu has been the subject of plays, films and television series, even though not much about Consort Yu was recorded in history. The story was reenacted on stage in the [[Peking opera]] ''[[The Hegemon-King Bids His Concubine Farewell]]''. Poets such as [[Su Shi]], He Pu and [[Yuan Mei]] have written poems about Consort Yu as well. Actresses such as [[Idy Chan]], [[Melissa Ng]], [[Kristy Yang]], [[Rosamund Kwan]] and [[Liu Yifei]] have played the role of Consort Yu in films and television series.\n\nIn the video game ''[[Fate/Grand Order]]'', Consort Yu is an Assassin-class Servant voiced by [[Mariya Ise]]. Here, she is a vampire who survived to the present day under the alias Hinako Akuta and desires to reunite with Xiang Yu, who is unexpectedly a monstrous robotic Centaur programmed by [[Qin Shi Huang]] under code name [[Huiji District|Huiji]]-Yishi.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n* [[Sima Qian]]. ''[[Records of the Grand Historian]]'', Volume 7, Biography of Xiang Yu.\n\n{{People of the Chu\u2013Han contention}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yu, Consort}}\n[[Category:202 BC deaths]]\n[[Category:Women in ancient Chinese warfare]]\n[[Category:Chu\u2013Han contention people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:3rd-century BC women writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consort_Yu"}
{"title_page": "Bangladesh University of Textiles", "text_new": "{{short description|public Textile Engineering university}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = {{nowrap|Bangladesh University of Textiles}}\n| other_name = BUTEX\n| former_name = {{Unbulleted list|British Weaving School {{small|(1921-1935)}}|East Bengal Textile Institute {{small|(1935-1950)}}|East Pakistan Textile Institute {{small|(1950-1978)}}|College of Textile Engineering and Technology {{small|(1978-2010)}}}}\n| image = BUTex_LOGO.png\n| native_name = \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u099f\u09c7\u0995\u09cd\u09b8\u099f\u09be\u0987\u09b2 \u09ac\u09bf\u09b6\u09cd\u09ac\u09ac\u09bf\u09a6\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b2\u09af\u09bc\n| native_name_lang = bn\n| caption = {{small|Official Logo}}\n| motto = ''Knowledge Is Power''\n| established = {{start date and age|df=yes|1921|12|22}} {{small|(latest upgradation in 2010)}}\n| type = [[Public university|Public]]\n| affiliation = {{Unbulleted list|[[Bangladesh Textile Mills Association|BTMA]]|[[Bangladesh Textile Mills Corporation|BTMC]]|[[Bangladesh Garment Manufacturers and Exporters Association|BGMEA]]|[[Bangladesh Knitwear Manufacturers and Exporters Association|BKMEA]]|[[Bangladesh Handloom Board|BHB]]|[[Bangladesh Jute Mills Association|BJMA]]|[[Bangladesh Jute Mills Corporation|BJMC]]|[[Bangladesh Jute Research Institute|BJRI]]|[[Bangladesh Sericulture Development Board|BSDB]]|[[Bangladesh Sericulture Research and Training Institute|BSRTI]]}}\n| academic_affiliation = {{Unbulleted list|[[Pabna Textile Engineering College|Pabtec]]|[[Textile Engineering College, Chittagong|Chattogram Textile Engineering College]]|[[Shaheed Abdur Rab Serniabat Textile Engineering College|SARSTEC]]|[[Begumgonj Textile Engineering College, Noakhali|Begumgonj Textile Engineering College]]|[[Bangabandhu Textile Engineering College]]|[[Sheikh Kamal Textile Engineering College]]|[[Dr. M A Wazed Miah Textile Engineering College|Dr. M A Wazed Miah Textile Engineering College]]}}\n| endowment = \n| provost = \n| dean = \n| budget = [[Bangladeshi taka|\u09f3]]190 million {{small|(per year)}}\n| officer_in_charge = \n| chancellor = [[Abdul Hamid (politician)|Mohammad Abdul Hamid]]\n| superintendent = \n| vice_chancellor = Prof. Engr. Md. Abul Kashem<ref name=\"Vice Chancellor\">{{cite web |url=http://www.butex.edu.bd/message-from-the-vice-chancellor-2/ |title=Message from the Vice Chancellor |website=Bangladesh University of Textiles}}</ref>\n| director = \n| academic_staff = 144\n| administrative_staff = 57\n| students = 2,790\n| undergrad = 2,640\n| postgrad = 150\n| doctoral = \n| campus = [[Urban area|Urban]], {{convert|11.67|acres}}\n| address = 92, Shaheed Tajuddin Ahmed AVE, [[Tejgaon]] Industrial Area\n| city = [[Dhaka]]\n| postalcode = 1208\n| country = [[Bangladesh]]\n| coordinates = \n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| free_label = Education System\n| free = [[Mixed-sex education|Co-education]]\n| free_label2 = Accreditation\n| free2 = {{plainlist |\n* [[Institution of Engineers, Bangladesh]]\n* [[Institution of Textile Engineers and Technologists]]\n* [[Bangladesh Accreditation Board]]\n}}\n| colors = Cardinal Red {{color box|#A31F34}}\n| sports = [[Association football|Football]], [[Volleyball]], [[Cricket]], [[Sport of athletics|Athletics]]\n| mascot = \n| sporting_affiliations = \n| website = {{URL|butex.edu.bd}}\n| logo = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Bangladesh University of Textiles''', commonly referred to as '''BUTEX''' ({{Lang-bn|\u09ac\u09c1\u099f\u09c7\u0995\u09cd\u09b8}}), is a Public Textile Engineering university in [[Bangladesh]] that emphasises on technological education in [[Textile|textiles]] while [[entrepreneurial]] [[industrialisation]] stays as its core subject of interest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prothomalo.com/education/article/1609828|title=\u2018\u09ae\u09c7\u0987\u09a1 \u0987\u09a8 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6\u2019 \u0997\u09b2\u09cd\u09aa\u09c7\u09b0 \u099a\u09b0\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09b0\u09be|last=|first=|date=|website=\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a5\u09ae \u0986\u09b2\u09cb ([[Prothom Alo]])|language=bn|trans-title=Heroes of 'Made in Bangladesh' story|publication-place=Bangladesh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/star-youth/dysin-texbiz-2018-1577899|title=Dysin Texbiz (2018) Launched|last=Staff correspondent at 'Star Youth'|first=|date=18 May 2018|work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=4 September 2019|url-status=live|publication-place=Bangladesh}}</ref>\n\nIt has seven [[Collegiate university|constituent college]] affiliated with it, all of which are textiles based [[Institute of technology|institutes of technology]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-95977|title=Form industrial police to protect RMG sector \u2014 Textile engineers urge government|last=Staff correspondent|first=|date=7 July 2009|work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=4 September 2019|url-status=live|publication-place=Bangladesh}}</ref> The colleges are centrally regulated by the university in a totalitarian manner, while the fundings are provided by the [[Department of Textiles|BD Department of Textiles]] under compliance with an [[Memorandum of understanding|MoU]] signed by the [[Ministry of Education (Bangladesh)|BD Ministry of Education]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-85952|title=RMG sector needs better technology \u2014 Says French business team leader|last=Star Business Report|first=|date=28 April 2009|work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=21 September 2019|url-status=live|publication-place=Bangladesh}}</ref>\n\nThe university itself offers academic and professional degrees in various fields of textiles technology, fashion designing, advanced business and marketing strategies and in several more disciplines on both undergraduate and postgraduate levels. {{As of|2018|November|df=|post=,}} it offers graduate programs in 10 different specialised areas under its five faculties.\n\n==History==\n\nThe institution was established as a fully functional university on 22 December 2010 by an ordinance of the Ministry of Education, [[Government of Bangladesh]].\n\n===British Weaving School===\n\nDuring the British colonial rule, in 1921, a weaving school was established at Narinda in the city of Dhaka to provide specialised technical education in the field of Textiles by offering artisan-level courses. It was named as British Weaving School and later East Bengal Textile Institute which was upgraded to offer diploma courses in Textile Technology. In 1950, it was once again renamed as East Pakistan Textile Institute. The institute was transferred to its present campus at [[Tejgaon]] Industrial Area in Dhaka in 1960.\n\n===College of Textile Engineering and Technology===\n\nIn the year of 1978, the institute launched a four-year period [[bachelor's degree]] program in Textile Technology by affiliation with the [[University of Dhaka]] and was upgraded into a college renaming it as College of Textile Engineering & Technology. Initially, intake was only 60 per year and since the introduction of bachelor's degree course, more than 2,800 textile engineers and technologists had graduated from this institution.\n\nThe erstwhile College of Textile Engineering & Technology had been an economically important institute under the administrative control of the [[Ministry of Education]] through Directorate of Technical Education which offered BSc in Textile Technology/BSc in Textile Engineering/BSc in Textile Management courses as a constituent college of the [[University of Dhaka]].\n\n===Birth of BUTEX===\n\nThe [[Bangladesh textile industry]] is the most important industrial sector as more than 83% of export earnings comes from this sector. Equipping the textile industry with qualified manpower with updated technical knowledge, expertise and skill is essential in building the appropriate backward linkages at the shortest possible time to face the challenges of quota-free post-MFA period.\n\nConsidering the importance of textile education and research, the government of Bangladesh took initiatives to upgrade the College of Textile Engineering & Technology to a university. For this purpose, \"Bangladesh Textile University Act, 2010\" (Act no. 49, 2010) was passed by the Bangladesh National Assembly and the Honorable President gave consent to the act on 5 October 2010. The Act was made effective from 22 December 2010 as per SRO No. 395-law/2010 date 20 December 2010 of the Ministry of Education. The Honorable Prime Minister of Bangladesh Sheikh Hasina officially inaugurated BUTEX on 15 March 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bdnews24.com/campus/2011/03/15/pm-opens-first-textile-university|title=PM opens first textile university|work=bdnews24.com|accessdate=16 June 2015}}</ref> \n[[File:Butex..jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Main Academic Building]]\n\n<br />\n\n==Academics==\n\n===Faculties and departments===\n\n*Faculty of '''Textile Engineering'''\n** Department of [[Spinning (textiles)|Yarn Engineering]] '''(YE)'''\n** Department of [[Textile manufacturing|Fabric Engineering]] '''(FE)'''\n*Faculty of '''Textile Chemicals Engineering'''\n** Department of [[Wet processing engineering|Wet Process Engineering]] '''(WPE)'''\n** Department of '''[[Chemical engineering|Dyes & Chemicals Engineering]] (DCE)'''\n** Department of '''[[Environmental science|Environmental Science & Engineering]] (ESE)'''\n*Faculty of '''Fashion Design & Apparel Engineering'''\n** Department of '''[[Clothing|Apparel Engineering]] (AE)'''\n** Department of [[Fashion design|Textile Fashion and Design]] '''(TFD)'''\n*Faculty of '''Textile Management & Business Studies'''\n** Department of '''[[Management science|Textile Engineering Management]] (TEM)'''\n** Department of [[Industrial and production engineering|Industrial and Production Engineering]] '''(IPE)'''\n*Faculty of '''Science & Engineering'''\n** Department of '''[[Mechanical engineering|Textile Machinery Design & Maintenance]] (TMDM)'''\n** Department of [[Physics]] '''(PHY)'''\n** Department of [[Chemistry]] '''(CHEM)'''\n** Department of [[Mathematics|Mathematics and Statistics]] '''(MS)'''\n** Department of [[Social science|Humanities & Social Sciences]] '''(HSS)'''\n\n==Student life==\n{{multiple image\n|image1 = Osmani...hall.jpg|width1=160|caption1= G M A G Osmani Hall\n|image2 = Aziz.hall.jpg|width2=120|caption2 = Shohid Aziz Hall\n}}\n\n===Halls of residence===\nThere are four residence halls to provide housing for BUTEX students. Administrative head of a residence hall is its respective [[provost (education)|provost]]. The Sheikh Hasina Hall is for female students, and the remaining two halls are for male students studying in the undergraduate level. The halls are named after historical eminent figures of Bangladesh (except the \"Sheikh Hasina Hall\"). They are listed below:\n\n* G M A G Osmani Hall ''(named after [[M. A. G. Osmani]] commander-in-chief of the Mukti Bahini during the 1971 Bangladesh Liberation War)''\n* Sheikh Hasina Hall\n* Syed Nazrul Islam Hall\n* Shahid Aziz Hall\n\n===Student organisations===\n*ARTex - Art Society of BUTEX\n*BUTEX Shahitto Shongshod\n* BUTEX Business Club<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.butexbc.com/ |title=BUTEX Business Club Website|work=Facebook|accessdate=22 Nov 2018}}</ref>\n*BUTEX Career Club\n* BUTEX Debating Society\n*BUTEX Film Society\n*BUTEX Journalist Society\n*BUTEX Science Club\n*BUTEX Photography Society\n*BUTEX Shuhrid Shomabesh\n* BUTEX Spinners Club<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/ekattor.butex|title=Ekattor cultural club|work=Facebook|accessdate=16 June 2015}}</ref>\n* BUTEX Wet Process Engineering Club\n*Ekattor - A cultural club of BUTEX\n* Toru - A Welfare Organization\n* Bauliana\n* Badhon (voluntary blood donor organisation), BUTEX Unit<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.badhan.com.bd/|title=BADHAN \u2013 A Voluntary Blood Donors'   Organization|publisher=|accessdate=16 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219040649/http://www.badhan.com.bd/|archive-date=19 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* BUTEX Bondhushova\n* BUTEX Gamer Maze\n* ExCa BUTEX\n* Phothik BUTEX \n* Youth Against Hunger (YAH), BUTEX Unit\n\n=== Sports facilities ===\nBUTEX has a playground at the middle of the campus. It is used as venue of annual athletics competition of the university as well as Inter departmental cricket, football competitions.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Mozaffar Hossain]], MEMBER OF PARLIAMENT, Jamalpur-5 , Jamalpur, Bangladesh Awami League and Founder of SIM GROUP\n\n* [[Rubayet Hossain]], Principal Data Scientist, National Auronatics of Space Administration (NASA), USA\n\n==See also==\n* [[Textile schools in Bangladesh]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.newagebd.net/article/65370/professor-abul-kashem-appointed-as-butex-vc Professor Md. Abul Kashem appointed as BUTEX VC]\n* [http://www.butex.edu.bd Official website of BUTex]\n* [http://www.textiletoday.com.bd Textile Based Magazine]\n* [http://bdnews24.com/campus/2011/03/15/pm-opens-first-textile-university PM opens first textile university]\n\n{{Public Universities of Bangladesh}}\n\n{{Coord|23.760367|N|90.400053|E|display=title|region:BD_type:city_source:enwiki}}\n\n[[Category:Public universities of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Textile industry of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Textile schools in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Dhaka]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|public Textile Engineering university}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = {{nowrap|Bangladesh University of Textiles}}\n| other_name = BUTEX\n| former_name = {{Unbulleted list|British Weaving School {{small|(1921-1935)}}|East Bengal Textile Institute {{small|(1935-1950)}}|East Pakistan Textile Institute {{small|(1950-1978)}}|College of Textile Engineering and Technology {{small|(1978-2010)}}}}\n| image = BUTex_LOGO.png\n| native_name = \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u099f\u09c7\u0995\u09cd\u09b8\u099f\u09be\u0987\u09b2 \u09ac\u09bf\u09b6\u09cd\u09ac\u09ac\u09bf\u09a6\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09b2\u09af\u09bc\n| native_name_lang = bn\n| caption = {{small|Official Logo}}\n| motto = ''Knowledge Is Power''\n| established = {{start date and age|df=yes|1921|12|22}} {{small|(latest upgradation in 2010)}}\n| type = [[Public university|Public]]\n| affiliation = {{Unbulleted list|[[Bangladesh Textile Mills Association|BTMA]]|[[Bangladesh Textile Mills Corporation|BTMC]]|[[Bangladesh Garment Manufacturers and Exporters Association|BGMEA]]|[[Bangladesh Knitwear Manufacturers and Exporters Association|BKMEA]]|[[Bangladesh Handloom Board|BHB]]|[[Bangladesh Jute Mills Association|BJMA]]|[[Bangladesh Jute Mills Corporation|BJMC]]|[[Bangladesh Jute Research Institute|BJRI]]|[[Bangladesh Sericulture Development Board|BSDB]]|[[Bangladesh Sericulture Research and Training Institute|BSRTI]]}}\n| academic_affiliation = {{Unbulleted list|[[Pabna Textile Engineering College|Pabtec]]|[[Textile Engineering College, Chittagong|Chattogram Textile Engineering College]]|[[Shaheed Abdur Rab Serniabat Textile Engineering College|SARSTEC]]|[[Begumgonj Textile Engineering College, Noakhali|Begumgonj Textile Engineering College]]|[[Bangabandhu Textile Engineering College]]|[[Sheikh Kamal Textile Engineering College]]|[[Dr. M A Wazed Miah Textile Engineering College|Dr M A Wazed Miah Textile Engineering College]]}}\n| endowment = \n| provost = \n| dean = \n| budget = [[Bangladeshi taka|\u09f3]]190 million {{small|(per year)}}\n| officer_in_charge = \n| chancellor = [[Abdul Hamid (politician)|Mohammad Abdul Hamid]]\n| superintendent = \n| vice_chancellor = Prof. Engr. Md. Abul Kashem<ref name=\"Vice Chancellor\">{{cite web |url=http://www.butex.edu.bd/message-from-the-vice-chancellor-2/ |title=Message from the Vice Chancellor |website=Bangladesh University of Textiles}}</ref>\n| director = \n| academic_staff = 144\n| administrative_staff = 57\n| students = 2,790\n| undergrad = 2,640\n| postgrad = 150\n| doctoral = \n| campus = [[Urban area|Urban]], {{convert|11.67|acres}}\n| address = 92, Shaheed Tajuddin Ahmed AVE, [[Tejgaon]] Industrial Area\n| city = [[Dhaka]]\n| postalcode = 1208\n| country = [[Bangladesh]]\n| coordinates = \n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| free_label = Education System\n| free = [[Mixed-sex education|Co-education]]\n| free_label2 = Accreditation\n| free2 = {{plainlist |\n* [[Institution of Engineers, Bangladesh]]\n* [[Institution of Textile Engineers and Technologists]]\n* [[Bangladesh Accreditation Board]]\n}}\n| colors = Cardinal Red {{color box|#A31F34}}\n| sports = [[Association football|Football]], [[Volleyball]], [[Cricket]], [[Sport of athletics|Athletics]]\n| mascot = \n| sporting_affiliations = \n| website = {{URL|butex.edu.bd}}\n| logo = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Bangladesh University of Textiles''', commonly referred to as '''BUTEX''' ({{Lang-bn|\u09ac\u09c1\u099f\u09c7\u0995\u09cd\u09b8}}), is a Public Textile Engineering university in [[Bangladesh]] that emphasises on technological education in [[Textile|textiles]] while [[entrepreneurial]] [[industrialisation]] stays as its core subject of interest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prothomalo.com/education/article/1609828|title=\u2018\u09ae\u09c7\u0987\u09a1 \u0987\u09a8 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6\u2019 \u0997\u09b2\u09cd\u09aa\u09c7\u09b0 \u099a\u09b0\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09b0\u09be|last=|first=|date=|website=\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a5\u09ae \u0986\u09b2\u09cb ([[Prothom Alo]])|language=bn|trans-title=Heroes of 'Made in Bangladesh' story|publication-place=Bangladesh|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/star-youth/dysin-texbiz-2018-1577899|title=Dysin Texbiz (2018) Launched|last=Staff correspondent at 'Star Youth'|first=|date=18 May 2018|work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=4 September 2019|url-status=live|publication-place=Bangladesh}}</ref>\n\nIt has seven [[Collegiate university|constituent college]] affiliated with it, all of which are textiles based [[Institute of technology|institutes of technology]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-95977|title=Form industrial police to protect RMG sector \u2014 Textile engineers urge government|last=Staff correspondent|first=|date=7 July 2009|work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=4 September 2019|url-status=live|publication-place=Bangladesh}}</ref> The colleges are centrally regulated by the university in a totalitarian manner, while the fundings are provided by the [[Department of Textiles|BD Department of Textiles]] under compliance with an [[Memorandum of understanding|MoU]] signed by the [[Ministry of Education (Bangladesh)|BD Ministry of Education]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-85952|title=RMG sector needs better technology \u2014 Says French business team leader|last=Star Business Report|first=|date=28 April 2009|work=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=21 September 2019|url-status=live|publication-place=Bangladesh}}</ref>\n\nThe university itself offers academic and professional degrees in various fields of textiles technology, fashion designing, advanced business and marketing strategies and in several more disciplines on both undergraduate and postgraduate levels. {{As of|2018|November|df=|post=,}} it offers graduate programs in 10 different specialised areas under its five faculties.\n\n==History==\n\nThe institution was established as a fully functional university on 22 December 2010 by an ordinance of the Ministry of Education, [[Government of Bangladesh]].\n\n===British Weaving School===\n\nDuring the British colonial rule, in 1921, a weaving school was established at Narinda in the city of Dhaka to provide specialised technical education in the field of Textiles by offering artisan-level courses. It was named as British Weaving School and later East Bengal Textile Institute which was upgraded to offer diploma courses in Textile Technology. In 1950, it was once again renamed as East Pakistan Textile Institute. The institute was transferred to its present campus at [[Tejgaon]] Industrial Area in Dhaka in 1960.\n\n===College of Textile Engineering and Technology===\n\nIn the year of 1978, the institute launched a four-year period [[bachelor's degree]] program in Textile Technology by affiliation with the [[University of Dhaka]] and was upgraded into a college renaming it as College of Textile Engineering & Technology. Initially, intake was only 60 per year and since the introduction of bachelor's degree course, more than 2,800 textile engineers and technologists had graduated from this institution.\n\nThe erstwhile College of Textile Engineering & Technology had been an economically important institute under the administrative control of the [[Ministry of Education]] through Directorate of Technical Education which offered BSc in Textile Technology/BSc in Textile Engineering/BSc in Textile Management courses as a constituent college of the [[University of Dhaka]].\n\n===Birth of BUTEX===\n\nThe [[Bangladesh textile industry]] is the most important industrial sector as more than 83% of export earnings comes from this sector. Equipping the textile industry with qualified manpower with updated technical knowledge, expertise and skill is essential in building the appropriate backward linkages at the shortest possible time to face the challenges of quota-free post-MFA period.\n\nConsidering the importance of textile education and research, the government of Bangladesh took initiatives to upgrade the College of Textile Engineering & Technology to a university. For this purpose, \"Bangladesh Textile University Act, 2010\" (Act no. 49, 2010) was passed by the Bangladesh National Assembly and the Honorable President gave consent to the act on 5 October 2010. The Act was made effective from 22 December 2010 as per SRO No. 395-law/2010 date 20 December 2010 of the Ministry of Education. The Honorable Prime Minister of Bangladesh Sheikh Hasina officially inaugurated BUTEX on 15 March 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bdnews24.com/campus/2011/03/15/pm-opens-first-textile-university|title=PM opens first textile university|work=bdnews24.com|accessdate=16 June 2015}}</ref> \n[[File:Butex..jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Main Academic Building]]\n\n<br />\n\n==Academics==\n\n===Faculties and departments===\n\n*Faculty of '''Textile Engineering'''\n** Department of [[Spinning (textiles)|Yarn Engineering]] '''(YE)'''\n** Department of [[Textile manufacturing|Fabric Engineering]] '''(FE)'''\n*Faculty of '''Textile Chemicals Engineering'''\n** Department of [[Wet processing engineering|Wet Process Engineering]] '''(WPE)'''\n** Department of '''[[Chemical engineering|Dyes & Chemicals Engineering]] (DCE)'''\n** Department of '''[[Environmental science|Environmental Science & Engineering]] (ESE)'''\n*Faculty of '''Fashion Design & Apparel Engineering'''\n** Department of '''[[Clothing|Apparel Engineering]] (AE)'''\n** Department of [[Fashion design|Textile Fashion and Design]] '''(TFD)'''\n*Faculty of '''Textile Management & Business Studies'''\n** Department of '''[[Management science|Textile Engineering Management]] (TEM)'''\n** Department of [[Industrial and production engineering|Industrial and Production Engineering]] '''(IPE)'''\n*Faculty of '''Science & Engineering'''\n** Department of '''[[Mechanical engineering|Textile Machinery Design & Maintenance]] (TMDM)'''\n** Department of [[Physics]] '''(PHY)'''\n** Department of [[Chemistry]] '''(CHEM)'''\n** Department of [[Mathematics|Mathematics and Statistics]] '''(MS)'''\n** Department of [[Social science|Humanities & Social Sciences]] '''(HSS)'''\n\n==Student life==\n{{multiple image\n|image1 = Osmani...hall.jpg|width1=160|caption1= G M A G Osmani Hall\n|image2 = Aziz.hall.jpg|width2=120|caption2 = Shohid Aziz Hall\n}}\n\n===Halls of residence===\nThere are four residence halls to provide housing for BUTEX students. Administrative head of a residence hall is its respective [[provost (education)|provost]]. The Sheikh Hasina Hall is for female students, and the remaining two halls are for male students studying in the undergraduate level. The halls are named after historical eminent figures of Bangladesh (except the \"Sheikh Hasina Hall\"). They are listed below:\n\n* G M A G Osmani Hall ''(named after [[M. A. G. Osmani]] commander-in-chief of the Mukti Bahini during the 1971 Bangladesh Liberation War)''\n* Sheikh Hasina Hall\n* Syed Nazrul Islam Hall\n* Shahid Aziz Hall\n\n===Student organisations===\n*ARTex - Art Society of BUTEX\n*BUTEX Shahitto Shongshod\n* BUTEX Business Club<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.butexbc.com/ |title=BUTEX Business Club Website|work=Facebook|accessdate=22 Nov 2018}}</ref>\n*BUTEX Career Club\n* BUTEX Debating Society\n*BUTEX Film Society\n*BUTEX Journalist Society\n*BUTEX Science Club\n*BUTEX Photography Society\n*BUTEX Shuhrid Shomabesh\n* BUTEX Spinners Club<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/ekattor.butex|title=Ekattor cultural club|work=Facebook|accessdate=16 June 2015}}</ref>\n* BUTEX Wet Process Engineering Club\n*Ekattor - A cultural club of BUTEX\n* Toru - A Welfare Organization\n* Bauliana\n* Badhon (voluntary blood donor organisation), BUTEX Unit<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.badhan.com.bd/|title=BADHAN \u2013 A Voluntary Blood Donors'   Organization|publisher=|accessdate=16 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219040649/http://www.badhan.com.bd/|archive-date=19 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* BUTEX Bondhushova\n* BUTEX Gamer Maze\n* ExCa BUTEX\n* Phothik BUTEX \n* Youth Against Hunger (YAH), BUTEX Unit\n\n=== Sports facilities ===\nBUTEX has a playground at the middle of the campus. It is used as venue of annual athletics competition of the university as well as Inter departmental cricket, football competitions.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Mozaffar Hossain]], MEMBER OF PARLIAMENT, Jamalpur-5 , Jamalpur, Bangladesh Awami League and Founder of SIM GROUP\n\n* [[Rubayet Hossain]], Principal Data Scientist, National Auronatics of Space Administration (NASA), USA\n\n==See also==\n* [[Textile schools in Bangladesh]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.newagebd.net/article/65370/professor-abul-kashem-appointed-as-butex-vc Professor Md. Abul Kashem appointed as BUTEX VC]\n* [http://www.butex.edu.bd Official website of BUTex]\n* [http://www.textiletoday.com.bd Textile Based Magazine]\n* [http://bdnews24.com/campus/2011/03/15/pm-opens-first-textile-university PM opens first textile university]\n\n{{Public Universities of Bangladesh}}\n\n{{Coord|23.760367|N|90.400053|E|display=title|region:BD_type:city_source:enwiki}}\n\n[[Category:Public universities of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Textile industry of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Textile schools in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Dhaka]]\n", "name_user": "Istiaque Hossain", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bangladesh_University_of_Textiles"}
