{"title_page": "Northern Mariana Islands/Transnational issues", "text_new": "#REDIRECT [[Northern Mariana Islands]]\n\n{{R from subpage}}\n", "text_old": "#REDIRECT [[Northern Mariana Islands]]\n", "name_user": "1234qwer1234qwer4", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:R from subpage", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Northern_Mariana_Islands/Transnational_issues&redirect=no"}
{"title_page": "John C. Fr\u00e9mont", "text_new": "{{short description|United States Army general and explorer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = John C. Fr\u00e9mont\n|image        = John Charles Fremont.jpg\n|office       = 5th [[List of Governors of Arizona|Governor]] of [[Arizona Territory]]\n|appointer    = [[Rutherford B. Hayes]]\n|term_start   = October 6, 1878\n|term_end     = October 11, 1881\n|predecessor  = [[John Philo Hoyt]]\n|successor    = [[Frederick Augustus Tritle]]\n|jr/sr1       = United States Senator\n|state1       = [[California]]\n|term_start1  = September 10, 1850\n|term_end1    = March 3, 1851\n|predecessor1 = Seat established\n|successor1   = [[John B. Weller]]\n|office2      = [[List of Governors of California before 1850|Military Governor of California]]\n|term_start2  = January 19, 1847\n|term_end2    = February 13, 1847\n|predecessor2 = [[Robert F. Stockton]]\n|successor2   = [[Stephen W. Kearny]]\n|birth_name   = John Charles Fr\u00e9mont\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1813|1|21}}\n|birth_place  = [[Savannah, Georgia]], U.S.\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|1890|7|13|1813|1|21}}\n|death_place  = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] (Before 1854)<br>[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] (1854\u20131864)<br>[[Radical Democracy Party (United States)|Radical Democracy]] (1864)\n|spouse       = [[Jessie Benton Fr\u00e9mont|Jessie Benton]]\n|relatives    = [[Thomas Hart Benton (politician)|Thomas Benton]] (father-in-law)\n|children     = 1\n|education    = [[College of Charleston]]\n|signature    = John C. Fr\u00e9mont Signature.svg\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch       = {{army|United States}}<br>[[Union Army]]\n|serviceyears = 1838\u20131848<br>1861\u20131864<br>1890\n|commands     = [[California Battalion]]<br>[[Department of the West]]\n|rank         = [[File:Union Army major general rank insignia.svg|border|35px]] [[Major general (United States)|Major General]]\n}}\n'''John Charles Fr\u00e9mont'''  or '''Fremont''' (January 21, 1813{{spaced ndash}}July 13, 1890) was an American [[List of explorers|explorer]], military officer, and politician. He was a [[United States Senate|US Senator]] from California, and in 1856 was the first [[History of the United States Republican Party|Republican]] nominee for [[President of the United States]]. \n\nA native of Georgia, Fr\u00e9mont acquired male protectors after his father's death, and became proficient in mathematics, science, and surveying. During the 1840s, he led five expeditions into the Western United States, and became known as ''The Pathfinder''.<ref>Allan Nevins, ''Fr\u00e9mont, the West's Greatest Adventurer: Being a Biography from Certain Hitherto Unpublished Sources of General John C. Fr\u00e9mont, Together with His Wife, Jessie Benton Fr\u00e9mont, and Some Account of the Period of Expansion which Found a Brilliant Leader in the Pathfinder'' (1928)</ref> During the [[Mexican\u2013American War]], Fr\u00e9mont, a major in the U.S. Army, took control of California from the [[California Republic]] in 1846. Fr\u00e9mont was convicted in [[court-martial]] for mutiny and insubordination after a conflict over who was the rightful [[California interim government, 1846\u20131850|military governor of California]]. After his sentence was commuted and he was reinstated by President [[James K. Polk|Polk]], Fr\u00e9mont resigned from the Army. Fr\u00e9mont led a private fourth expedition, which cost ten lives, seeking a rail route over the mountains around the [[38th parallel north|38th parallel]] in the winter of 1849. \n\nAfterwards, Fr\u00e9mont settled in California at [[Monterey, California|Monterey]] while buying cheap land in the Sierra foothills. When gold was found on his Mariposa ranch, Fr\u00e9mont became a wealthy man during the [[California Gold Rush]], but he was soon bogged down with lawsuits over land claims, between the dispossession of various land owners during the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] and the explosion of [[California Gold Rush#Forty-niners|Forty-Niners]] immigrating during the Rush. These cases were settled by the U.S. Supreme Court allowing Fr\u00e9mont to keep his property. Fr\u00e9mont's fifth and final privately funded expedition, between 1853 and 1854, surveyed a route for a transcontinental railroad. Fr\u00e9mont became one of the first two U.S. senators elected from the new state of California in 1850. Fr\u00e9mont was the first presidential candidate of the new [[History of the United States Republican Party|Republican Party]], carrying most of the North. He lost the [[1856 United States presidential election|1856 presidential election]] to Democrat [[James Buchanan]] when [[Know Nothing]]s split the vote. At the beginning of the [[American Civil War]] in 1861, he was given command of [[Department of the West]] by President [[Abraham Lincoln]]. \n\nAlthough Fr\u00e9mont had successes during his brief tenure there, he ran his department autocratically, and made hasty decisions without consulting President Lincoln or Army headquarters. He issued an unauthorized emancipation edict and was relieved of his command for insubordination by Lincoln. Fr\u00e9mont appointed future commander-in-chief [[Ulysses S. Grant]] to his first command (the strategically important city of [[Cairo, Illinois]]), and wrote later that he saw in Grant an \"iron will\" to fight. Fr\u00e9mont drove the Confederates out of southwest Missouri and [[Action at Springfield|reoccupied Springfield]], the only Union success in the West in 1861. After a brief service tenure in the Mountain Department in 1862, Fr\u00e9mont resided in New York, retiring from the Army in 1864. Fr\u00e9mont was nominated for President in 1864 by the [[Radical Democracy Party (United States)|Radical Democracy Party]], a breakaway faction of abolitionist Republicans, but he withdrew before the election. After the Civil War, Fr\u00e9mont lost much of his wealth in the unsuccessful [[Pacific Railroad]] in 1866, and lost more in the [[Panic of 1873]]. Fr\u00e9mont served as Governor of Arizona from 1878 to 1881. After his resignation as governor, Fr\u00e9mont retired from politics and died destitute in New York City in 1890.\n\nHistorians portray Fr\u00e9mont as controversial, impetuous, and contradictory. Some scholars regard him as a military hero of significant accomplishment, while others view him as a failure who repeatedly defeated his own best purposes. The keys to Fr\u00e9mont's character and personality may lie in his having been born illegitimately, ambitious drive for success, self-justification, and passive\u2013aggressive behavior.<ref>Andrew Rolle, \"Exploring an Explorer: California, Psychohistory, and John C. Fremont\", ''Southern California Quarterly'', March 1994, Vol. 76#1 pp. 85\u201398</ref><ref>Andrew F. Rolle, ''John Charles Fremont: Character As Destiny'' (1991)</ref> Fr\u00e9mont's published reports and maps produced from his explorations significantly contributed to massive American emigration overland into the West starting in the 1840s. In June 1846, Fr\u00e9mont's and his army expedition's return to California spurred the formation of the [[California Battalion]], and his military advice led to the capture of Sonoma and the formation of the [[Bear Flag Republic]]. During his lifetime, many people believed his 1848 court martial was unjustified. His biographer [[Allan Nevins]] wrote that Fr\u00e9mont lived a dramatic life, of remarkable successes and dismal failures.\n\n==Early life, education, and career==\nJohn Charles Fr\u00e9mont was born on January 21, 1813, the son of Charles Fr\u00e9mon, a [[French-Canadian]] immigrant school-teacher,{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=19}}<ref>Chaffin, pp. 21\u201322</ref>{{efn|According to biographer Andrew F. Rolle (1991) Fr\u00e9mont's father was born in Qu\u00e9bec City, Canada, on December 8, 1768, and originally named Louis-Ren\u00e9 Fr\u00e9mont<ref name=Rolle1991>{{cite book |last=Rolle |first=Andrew |title=John Charles Fr\u00e9mont: Character as Destiny |url=https://archive.org/details/johncharlesfremo0000roll |url-access=registration |publisher=University of Oklahoma Press |location=Norman |year=1991 |isbn=0-585-35954-7 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/johncharlesfremo0000roll/page/n31 2]\u20135}}</ref>{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=19}} Louis-Ren\u00e9 left Canada on a French ship and was voyaging to Santo Domingo when he was arrested by the British man-of-war and imprisoned in the British West Indies.<ref name=Rolle1991/> After Louis-Ren\u00e9 escaped imprisonment by the British, he settled in Norfork, Virginia calling himself Charles Fr\u00e9mon.<ref name=Rolle1991/> To avoid recapture by the British, Fr\u00e9mon informed people he was born in Lyon France, fought in the French Revolution aiding the Royalists, and was on his way to Santo Domingo when he was captured by the British.<ref name=Rolle1991/> Historian H. W. Brands (2005) said Fr\u00e9mont added the accented E and the T to his surname later in life.<ref>{{cite book |last=Brands |first=H. W. |title=Andrew Jackson, His Life and Times |publisher=Doubleday |location=Garden City |year=2005 |isbn=0-385-50738-0 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780385507387/page/188 188\u201390] |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780385507387/page/188 }}</ref> Rolle, however, said Fr\u00e9mont began using the accent in 1838 at the age of 25.<ref name=Rolle1991/>}} and Anne Beverley Whiting, the youngest daughter of socially prominent Virginia planter Col. Thomas Whiting. At age 17, Anne married [[Major John Pryor]], a wealthy Richmond resident in his early 60s. In 1810, Pryor hired Fr\u00e9mon to tutor his young wife Anne. Pryor confronted Anne when he found out she was having an affair with Fr\u00e9mon. Anne and Fr\u00e9mon fled to Williamsburg on July 10, 1811, later settling in [[Norfolk, Virginia]], taking with them household slaves Anne had inherited.<ref>Nevins pp. 3\u20137. Chaffin pp. 19\u201321</ref><ref name=Rolle1991/> The couple later settled in [[Savannah, Georgia]], where she gave birth to their son Fr\u00e9mont out of wedlock.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=19}} Pryor published a divorce petition in the ''Virginia Patriot'', and charged that his wife had \"for some time past indulged in criminal intercourse\". When the Virginia House of Delegates refused Anne's divorce petition, it was impossible for the couple to marry. In Savannah, Anne took in boarders while Fr\u00e9mon taught French and dancing. A woman enslaved in the household, Black Hannah, helped raise young John.<ref name=Rolle1991/>\n\n[[image:JRP-SoW, S.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Joel R. Poinsett]], a wealthy South Carolinian, was Fr\u00e9mont's patron.]]\nOn December 8, 1818, Fr\u00e9mont's father Fr\u00e9mon died in [[Norfolk, Virginia]], leaving Anne a widow to take care of John and several young children alone on a limited inherited income.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=19}} Anne and her family moved to [[Charleston, South Carolina]]. Fr\u00e9mont, knowing his origins and coming from relatively modest means, grew up a proud, reserved, restless loner who although self-disciplined, was ready to prove himself and unwilling to play by the rules.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=43}} The young Fr\u00e9mont was considered to be \"precious, handsome, and daring,\" having the ability of obtaining protectors.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=19}} A lawyer, John W. Mitchell, provided for Fr\u00e9mont's early education whereupon Fr\u00e9mont in May 1829 entered [[College of Charleston|Charleston College]], teaching at intervals in the countryside, but was expelled for irregular attendance in 1831. Fr\u00e9mont, however, had been grounded in mathematics and natural sciences.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=19}}\n\nFr\u00e9mont attracted the attention of eminent South Carolina politician [[Joel Roberts Poinsett|Joel R. Poinsett]], an [[Andrew Jackson]] supporter, who secured Fr\u00e9mont an appointment as a teacher of mathematics aboard the [[Sloop-of-war|sloop]] [[USS Natchez (1827)|USS ''Natchez'']], sailing the South American seas in 1833.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=44}} Fr\u00e9mont resigned from the navy and was appointed second lieutenant in the [[Corps of Topographical Engineers|United States Topographical Corps]], [[surveying]] a route for the Charleston, Louisville, and Cincinnati railroad.{{sfnm|Richardson|2007|1p=44|Nevins|1931|2p=19}} Working in the Carolina mountains, Fr\u00e9mont desired to become an explorer.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=19}} Between 1837 and 1838, Fr\u00e9mont's desire for exploration increased while in Georgia on reconnaissance to prepare for the removal of [[Trail of Tears|Cherokee Indians]].{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=19}}  When Poinsett became Secretary of War, he arranged for Fr\u00e9mont to assist notable French explorer and scientist [[Joseph Nicollet]] in exploring the lands between the [[Mississippi River|Mississippi]] and [[Missouri River|Missouri]] rivers.{{sfn|Richardson|2007|p=44}} Fr\u00e9mont became a first rate topographer, trained in astronomy, and geology, describing fauna, flora, soil, and water resources.{{sfnm|Richardson|2007|1p=44|Nevins|1931|2p=20}} Gaining valuable western frontier experience Fr\u00e9mont came in contact with notable men including [[Henry Hastings Sibley|Henry Sibley]], [[Joseph Renville]], [[Jean-Baptiste Faribault|J.B. Faribault]], [[\u00c9tienne Provost]], and the [[Sioux]] nation.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=20}}\n[[image:Thomas Hart Benton daguerreotype.jpeg|thumb|150px|left|[[Thomas Hart Benton (politician)|Thomas Hart Benton]], U.S. Senator, Missouri, was Fr\u00e9mont's powerful backer in the Senate.]]\n[[File:Jessie Benton Fremont.jpg|thumb|150px|right|[[Jessie Benton Fremont]]]]\n\n==Marriage and senatorial patronage==\nFr\u00e9mont's exploration work with Nicollet brought him in contact with Senator [[Thomas Hart Benton (senator)|Thomas Hart Benton]] of Missouri, powerful chairman of the Senate Committee on Military Affairs.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=44}} Benton invited Fr\u00e9mont to his Washington home where he met Benton's 16-year-old daughter [[Jessie Benton Fr\u00e9mont|Jessie Benton]].{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=44}} A romance blossomed between the two; however, Benton was initially against it because Fr\u00e9mont was not considered upper society.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=44}} In 1841, Fr\u00e9mont (age 28) and Jessie eloped and were married by a Catholic priest.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=44}}<ref name=\"appletons\" /> Initially Benton was furious at their marriage, but in time, because he loved his daughter, he accepted their marriage and became Fr\u00e9mont's patron.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=44}} Benton, [[History of the Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] leader for more than 30 years in the Senate, championed the expansionist movement, a political cause that became known as [[Manifest Destiny]].{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=44}} The expansionists believed that the North American continent, from one end to the other, north and south, east and west, should belong to the citizens of the U.S. They believed it was the nation's destiny to control the continent. This movement became a crusade for politicians such as Benton and his new son-in-law. Benton pushed appropriations through Congress for national surveys of the [[Oregon Trail]], the [[Oregon Country]], the [[Great Basin]], and [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada Mountains]] to California. Through his power and influence, Senator Benton obtained for Fr\u00e9mont the leadership, funding, and patronage of three expeditions.\n\n==Fr\u00e9mont's explorations==\n{{see also|Westward Expansion Trails|Manifest Destiny}}\n[[File:General John Charles Fr\u00e9mont Healy Unknown Date.JPG|thumb|200px|<center>John C. Fr\u00e9mont</center><center>by [[George Peter Alexander Healy|George Healy]] ''unknown date''</center>]]\nThe opening of the American West began in 1804, when the [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]] ([[Meriwether Lewis]] and [[William Clark]]) started exploration of the new [[Louisiana Purchase]] territory to find a northwest passage up the [[Missouri River]] to the [[Pacific Ocean]]. President [[Thomas Jefferson]] had envisioned a Western empire, and also sent the [[Pike Expedition]] under [[Zebulon Pike]] to explore the southwest.<ref name=Rhonda_2012_p64>Rhonda (2012), p.&nbsp;64</ref> British and American [[fur trade|fur trappers]], including [[Peter Skene Ogden]] and [[Jedediah Smith]], explored much of the American West in the 1820s.<ref name=Beck_1989_27>Beck (1989), pp. 27\u201328</ref><ref name=Barbour_2012_p5>Barbour (2012), p. 5</ref><ref name=Morgan_1953_p7>Morgan (1953), p. 7</ref>{{efn|As early as 1831, Smith had made a map of the West and had requested Andrew Jackson's Secretary of War [[John H. Eaton]] for a formal federal exploration party. Eaton resigned, however, and Smith was killed by Comanches, and nothing became of the expedition. Smith's map would later be superimposed by George Gibbs on a base map by Fr\u00e9mont.}} Fr\u00e9mont, who would later be known as ''The Pathfinder'', carried on this tradition of Western overland exploration, building on and adding to the work of earlier pathfinders to expand knowledge of the American West.{{sfn|McNamara|2016}} Fr\u00e9mont's talent lay in his scientific documentation, publications, and maps made based on his expeditions, making the American West accessible for many Americans.{{sfn|McNamara|2016}} Beginning in 1842, Fr\u00e9mont led five western expeditions, however, between the third and fourth expeditions, Fr\u00e9mont's career took a fateful turn because of the [[Mexican\u2013American War]]. Fr\u00e9mont's initial explorations, his timely scientific reports, co-authored by his wife Jessie, and their romantic writing style, encouraged Americans to travel West.{{sfn|Richards|2007|pp=46\u201347}} A series of seven maps produced from his findings, published by the Senate in 1846, served as a guide for thousands of American emigrants, depicting the entire length of the [[Oregon Trail]].{{sfn|Richards|2007|pp=46\u201347}}\n\n===First expedition (1842)===\n[[image:Carsonfremont.jpg|180px|thumb|left|Fr\u00e9mont (seated right)<br>and [[Kit Carson]], Fr\u00e9mont's expeditions guide. ]]\nWhen Nicollet was too ill to continue any further explorations, Fr\u00e9mont was chosen to be his successor.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=20}} His first important expedition was planned by Benton, Senator [[Lewis F. Linn|Lewis Linn]], and other Westerners interested in acquiring the Oregon Territory.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=20}} The scientific expedition started in the summer of 1842 and was to explore the [[Wind River (Wyoming)|Wind River]] of the [[Rocky Mountains]], examine the [[Oregon Trail]] through the [[South Pass (Wyoming)|South Pass]], and report on the rivers and the fertility of the lands, find optimal sites for forts, and describe the mountains beyond in Wyoming.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=20}} By chance meeting, Fr\u00e9mont was able to gain the valuable assistance of mountain man and guide [[Kit Carson]].{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=20}} Fr\u00e9mont and his party of 25 men, including Carson, embarked from the [[Kansas River]] on June 15, 1842, following the [[Platte River]] to the South Pass, and starting from [[Green River (Colorado River)|Green River]] he explored the [[Wind River Range]].{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=20}} Fr\u00e9mont climbed a 13,745-foot mountain, ''[[Fremont Peak (Wyoming)|Fr\u00e9mont's Peak]]'', planted an American flag, claiming the Rocky Mountains and the West for the United States.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=20}} On Fr\u00e9mont's return trip he and his party carelessly rafted the swollen Platte River losing much of his equipment.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=20}} His five-month exploration, however, was a success, returning to Washington in October.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=20}} Fr\u00e9mont and his wife Jessie wrote a ''Report of the Exploring Expedition to the Rocky Mountains'' (1843), which was printed in newspapers across the country; the public embraced his vision of the west not as a place of danger but wide open and inviting lands to be settled.<ref name=hamptonsides>{{cite book |title=Blood and Thunder |publisher=Anchor Books |author=Hampton Sides |year=2006 |page=82 |author-link=Hampton Sides }}</ref>{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=20}}{{efn|As [[Hampton Sides]] says, \"Fr\u00e9mont became an instant celebrity, a champion of expansion, a conqueror wielding not a sword but a compass and a transit.\"<ref name=hamptonsides /> [[Henry Wadsworth Longfellow]] said after the report, \"Fr\u00e9mont has touched my imagination. What a wild life, and what a fresh kind of existence! But ah, the discomforts!\"<ref name=hamptonsides />}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===Second expedition (1843\u20131844)===\n{{see|Oregon Trail|Mexican California|Oregon Country|Treaty of 1818}}\nFr\u00e9mont's successful first expedition led quickly to a second; it began in the summer of 1843.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=20}} The more ambitious goal this time was to  map and describe the second half of the Oregon Trail, find an alternate route to the South Pass, and push westward toward the Pacific Ocean on the Columbia River in Oregon Country.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=20}} Fr\u00e9mont and his almost 40 well-equipped men, left the Missouri River in May after he controversially obtained a 12-pound [[Howitzer|howitzer cannon]] in St. Louis.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=20}} Fr\u00e9mont invited Carson on the second expedition, due to his proven skills, and he joined Fr\u00e9mont's party on the Arkansas River.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=20}} Unable to find a new route through Colorado to the South Pass, Fr\u00e9mont took to the regular Oregon Trail, passing the main body of the great immigration of 1843.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=20}} His party stopped to explore the northern part of the [[Great Salt Lake]], then traveling by way [[Fort Hall]] and [[Fort Boise]] to [[Marcus Whitman]]'s mission, along the [[Snake River]] to the [[Columbia River]] and in to Oregon.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=20}} Fr\u00e9mont's endurance, energy, and resourcefulness over the long journey was remarkable.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=20}} Traveling west along the Columbia, they came within sight of the [[Cascade Range]] peaks and mapped [[Mount St. Helens]] and [[Mount Hood]]. Reaching the Dalles on November 5, Fr\u00e9mont left his party and traveled to British [[Fort Vancouver]] for supplies.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=20}}\n\n[[image:Sutter's Fort from Gleason's Pictorial Drawing Room Companion.jpg|220px |thumb |right |Fr\u00e9mont's second expedition party reached '''Sutter's Fort''' in the [[Sacramento Valley]] in March 1844]]\n\nRather than turning around and heading back to St. Louis, Fr\u00e9mont resolved to explore the Great Basin between the Rockies and the Sierras and fulfill Benton's dream of acquiring the West for the United States.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} Fr\u00e9mont and his party turned south along the eastern flank of the Cascades through the Oregon territory to [[Pyramid Lake (Nevada)|Pyramid Lake]], which he named.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} Looping back to the east to stay on the eastern side of the [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]] mountain range, they turned south again as far as present-day [[Minden, Nevada]], reaching the Carson River on January 18, 1844.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} From an area near what later became Virginia City, Fr\u00e9mont daringly, possibly foolhardily, turned west into the cold and snowy Sierra Nevada, becoming one of the first Americans to see [[Lake Tahoe]].{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} Carson successfully led Fr\u00e9mont's party through a new pass over the high Sierras, which Fr\u00e9mont named [[Carson Pass]] in his honor. Fr\u00e9mont and his party then descended the [[American River]] valley to [[Sutter's Fort]] (Spanish: Nueva Helvetia) at present-day [[Sacramento, California]] in early March.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} Captain [[John Sutter]], a German-Mexican (and later American by [[Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo|treaty]]) immigrant and founder of the fort, received Fr\u00e9mont gladly and refitted his expedition party.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} While at Sutter's Fort, Fr\u00e9mont talked to American settlers, who were growing numerous, and found that Mexican authority over California was very weak.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}}\n\nLeaving Sutter's Fort, Fr\u00e9mont and his men headed south following Smith's trail on the eastern edge of the [[San Joaquin Valley]] until he struck the \"''[[Old Spanish Trail (trade route)|Spanish Trail]]''\" between Los Angeles and Santa Fe, and headed east through [[Tehachapi Pass]] and present-day [[Las Vegas]] before regaining Smith's trail north through Utah and back to South Pass.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} Exploring the [[Great Basin]], Fr\u00e9mont verified that all the land (centered on modern-day Nevada between Reno and Salt Lake City) was [[Endorheic basin|endorheic]], without any outlet rivers flowing towards the sea. The finding contributed greatly to a better understanding of North American geography, and disproved a longstanding legend of a '[[Buenaventura River (legend)|Buenaventura River]]' that flowed out the Great Basin across the Sierra Nevada. After exploring Utah Lake, Fr\u00e9mont traveled by way of the Pueblo until he reached Bent's Fort on the Arkansas River.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} In August 1844, Fr\u00e9mont and his party finally arrived back in St. Louis, enthusiastically received by the people, ending the journey that lasted over one year.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} His wife Jessie and Fr\u00e9mont returned to Washington, where the two wrote a second report, scientific in detail, showing the Oregon Trail was not difficult to travel and that the Northwest had fertile land.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} Senator Buchanan ordered the printing of 10,000 copies to be used by settlers and fervor the popular movement of national expansion.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}}{{efn|Upon his return, Fr\u00e9mont produced a new map in 1845 that included the second expedition, and Fr\u00e9mont's conclusion that the still-unmapped areas of the Great Basin were \"...believed to be filled with lakes and rivers which have no communication with the sea...\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://maps.bpl.org/id/16061 |title='' Map of an exploring expedition to the Rocky Mountains in the year 1842 and to Oregon & North California in the years 1843\u201344'' |author=John Charles Fr\u00e9mont |year=1845 |website=Norman B. Leventhal map Center |publisher=Boston Public Library |accessdate=March 8, 2014}}</ref> Congress published Fr\u00e9mont's \"Report and Map\"; it guided thousands of overland immigrants to Oregon and California from 1845 to 1849. In 1849 Joseph Ware published his ''Emigrants' Guide to California''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/emigrantsguideto00dist#page/n3/mode/2up|title=The emigrant's guide to New Mexico, California, and Oregon|publisher=}} {{OCLC|2356459}},</ref> which was largely drawn from Fr\u00e9mont's report, and was to guide the forty-niners through the [[California Gold Rush]]. Fr\u00e9mont's report was more than a travelers' guide&nbsp;\u2013 it was a government publication that achieved the expansionist objectives of a nation and provided scientific and economic information concerning the potential of the trans-Mississippi West for pioneer settlement.<ref>Stephen Craig Weiss, \"The John C. Fremont '1842, 1843\u2013'44 Report' and Map,\" ''Journal of Government Information'', May 1999, Vol. 26#3 pp. 297\u2013313</ref> For his expeditionary work, he received a brevet promotion to captain in July 1844. One of Fr\u00e9mont's reports from an expedition inspired the [[Mormons]] to consider [[Utah]] for settlement.<ref name=\"appletons\">{{Cite Appletons'|wstitle=Fr\u00e9mont, John Charles|year=1900}}</ref>}}\n\n===Third expedition (1845)===\n\nWith the backdrop of an impending war with Mexico, after [[James K. Polk]] had been elected president, Benton quickly organized a third expedition for Fr\u00e9mont.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} The plan for Fr\u00e9mont under the War Department was to survey the central Rockies, the Great Salt Lake region, and part of the Sierra Nevada.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} Back in St. Louis, Fr\u00e9mont organized an armed surveying expedition of 60 men, with Carson as a guide, and two distinguished scouts, [[Joseph R. Walker|Joseph Walker]] and Alexander Godey.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} Working with Benton and Secretary of Navy [[George Bancroft]], Fr\u00e9mont was secretly told that if war started with Mexico he was to turn his scientific expedition into a military force.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} President Polk, who had met with Fr\u00e9mont at a cabinet meeting, was set on taking California.{{sfn|Denton|2011}} Fr\u00e9mont desired to conquer California for its beauty and wealth, and would later explain his very controversial conduct there.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}}\n\nOn June 1, 1845, Fr\u00e9mont and his armed expedition party left St. Louis having the immediate goal to locate the source of the [[Arkansas River]], on the east side of the Rocky Mountains.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Janin|first1=Hunt|last2=Carlson|first2=Ursula|title=Trails of Historic New Mexico: Routes Used by Indian, Spanish and American Travelers Through 1886|year=2009|publisher=McFarland|page=81|isbn=978-0-7864-4010-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S4u42zsVr04C&pg=PA81}}</ref>{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} Fr\u00e9mont and his party struck west by way of Bent's Fort, The Great Salt Lake, and the \"Hastings Cut-Off\".{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} When Fr\u00e9mont reached the Ogden River, which he renamed the [[Humboldt River|Humboldt]], he divided his party in two to double his geographic information.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} Upon reaching the Arkansas River, Fr\u00e9mont suddenly made a blazing trail through Nevada straight to California, having a rendezvous with his men from the split party at [[Walker Lake (Nevada)|Walker Lake]] in west-central Nevada.{{sfnm|Nevins|1931|1p=21|Walker|1999|2p=84}}{{efn|No formal record of Fr\u00e9mont's third expedition was ever made, as in his previous expeditions, or when it actually ended. Fr\u00e9mont, however, did help his cartographer [[Charles Preuss]] make a map of Upper Oregon and California.{{sfn|Fr\u00e9mont|1973|p=xlvi}} Additionally, hundreds of species of plants in two huge cases from Bent's Fort and San Francisco were sent back east to botanist [[John Torrey]] by the [[USS Erie (1813)|USS ''Erie'']].{{sfn|Fr\u00e9mont|1973|p=xlvi}}}}\n\n==Events in California and Oregon Country (1845\u20131846)==\nTaking 16 men, Fr\u00e9mont split his party again, arriving at Sutter's Fort in the [[Sacramento Valley]] on December 9.{{sfnm|Nevins|1931|1p=21|Walker|1999|2p=84}} Fr\u00e9mont promptly sought to stir up patriotic enthusiasm among the American settlers there. He promised that if war with Mexico started, his military force would protect the settlers.<ref>{{cite book|last=Sides|first=Hampton|title=Blood and Thunder: An Epic of the American West|year=2006|publisher=Random House|pages=123\u201324|isbn=978-0-7393-2672-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oUiwaEzbgeMC&pg=PA123}}</ref> Fr\u00e9mont went to [[Monterey, California]], to talk with the American consul, [[Thomas O. Larkin]], and Mexican ''commandant'' [[Jos\u00e9 Castro|Jose Castro]], under the pretext of gaining fuller supplies.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} In February 1846, Fr\u00e9mont reunited with 45 men of his expedition party near San Jose Mission, giving the United States a formidable military army in California.{{sfnm|Nevins|1931|1p=21|Walker|1999|2p=92}} Castro and Mexican officials were suspicious of Fr\u00e9mont and he was ordered to leave the country.{{sfn|Denton|2011|p=35}}{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} Fr\u00e9mont and his men withdrew and camped near the summit of what is now named [[Fremont Peak (California)|Fremont Peak]]. Headstrong and with much audacity, Fr\u00e9mont raised the United States Flag in defiance of Mexican authority.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} Playing for time, after a four-day standoff and Castro having a superior number of Mexican troops, Fr\u00e9mont and his men went north to Oregon, conducting the [[Sacramento River massacre]] along the way. They eventually made camp at [[Upper Klamath Lake|Klamath Lake]].<ref>Sides, 2006, p. 124</ref><ref>Sides, 2006, pp. 124\u201325</ref>{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}}\n\n[[image: John C. Fr\u00e9mont attacked by Indians.jpg|thumb|right|Fr\u00e9mont, attacked by Indians]]\n\nOn May 8, Fr\u00e9mont was overtaken by Lieutenant [[Archibald H. Gillespie|Archibald Gillespie]] from Washington, who gave him copies of dispatches he had previously given to Larkin.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} Gillespie told Fr\u00e9mont secret instructions from Benton and Buchanan justifying aggressive action and that a declaration of war with Mexico was imminent.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} On May 9, 1846, Indians attacked his expedition party in retaliation for numerous killings of Indians that Fr\u00e9mont's men had engaged in along the trail. Fr\u00e9mont retaliated by attacking a [[Klamath people|Klamath]] Indian fishing village named ''Dokdokwas'' the following day in the [[Klamath Lake massacre]], although the people living there might not have been involved in the first action.<ref name=\"Sides154\">Sides, 2006, p. 154</ref> The village was at the junction of the [[Williamson River (Oregon)|Williamson River]] and Klamath Lake. On May 12, 1846, the Fr\u00e9mont group completely destroyed it.<ref>Sides, 2006, p. 153</ref> Fr\u00e9mont believed that the British were responsible for arming and encouraging the Indians to attack his American party.{{sfn|Fr\u00e9mont|1973|pp=xx, xxi}} Afterward, Carson was nearly killed by a Klamath warrior. As Carson's gun misfired, the warrior drew to shoot a poison arrow; however, Fr\u00e9mont, seeing that Carson was in danger, trampled the warrior with his horse. Carson felt that he owed Fr\u00e9mont his life.<ref name=\"Sides154\" /> A few weeks later, Fr\u00e9mont and his armed militia returned to California.{{sfnm|Richardson|2007|1p=45|Denton|2011}}\n\n==Mexican\u2013American War (1846\u20131848)==\n{{see|California Republic|Conquest of California|Mexican\u2013American War}}\n\nHaving reentered Mexican California headed south, Fr\u00e9mont and his army expedition stopped off at [[Peter Lassen]]'s Ranch on May 24, 1846.{{sfn|Walker|1999|pp=108, 116}} Fr\u00e9mont learned from Lassen that the [[USS Portsmouth (1843)|USS ''Portsmouth'']], commanded by [[John B. Montgomery]], was anchored at [[Sausalito, California|Sausalito]].{{sfn|Walker|1999|pp=108, 116}} Fr\u00e9mont sent Lt. Gillespie to Montgomery and requested supplies including 8000 percussion caps, 300 pounds of rifle lead, one keg of powder, and food provisions, intending to head back to St. Louis.{{sfn|Walker|1999|pp=108, 116}} On May 31, Fr\u00e9mont made his camp on the Bear and Feather rivers 60 miles north of [[Sutter's Fort]], where American Californians ready for revolt against Mexican authority joined his party.{{sfnm|Denton|2011|Nevins|1931|2p=21|Walker|1999|p=116}} From there he made another attack on local Indians in a rancheria (see [[Sutter Buttes massacre]]).{{sfn|Fr\u00e9mont|1887|pp=516\u201317}} In early June, believing war with Mexico to be a virtual certainty, Fr\u00e9mont joined the Sacramento Valley insurgents in a \"silent partnership\", rather than head back to St. Louis, as originally planned.{{sfn|Walker|1999|pp=108, 116\u201317}}{{sfn|Walker|1999|pp=120, 122}} On June 10, ordered by Fr\u00e9mont, four men from Fr\u00e9mont's party and 10 rebel volunteers seized 170 horses intended for Castro's Army and returned them to Fr\u00e9mont's camp.{{sfnm|Denton|2011|Walker|1999|2pp=120\u201322|Bancroft|1886|3p=107}} On June 14, having been [[military advisor|advised and ordered]] by Fr\u00e9mont, 34 armed rebels independently captured Sonoma, the largest settlement in northern California, and forced the surrender of Colonel [[Mariano Vallejo]], taking him and three others prisoners.{{sfnm|Denton|2011|Nevins|1931|2p=21|Walker|1999|3pp=121\u201323|Bancroft|1886|4p=109}} The following day, rebel Californians who called themselves ''Osos'' (Spanish for \"bears\"), amidst a brandy-filled party, hoisted a roughly sewn flag, and formed the [[Bear Flag Republic]], electing [[William Ide]] as their leader.{{sfnm|Denton|2011|Nevins|1931|2p=21|Walker|1999|3pp=123\u201325, 128}} The four prisoners were then taken to Fr\u00e9mont's American camp 80 miles away.{{sfn|Walker|1999|pp=123\u201325, 128}} On June 15, the prisoners and escorts arrived at Fr\u00e9mont's new camp on the American River, but Fr\u00e9mont publicly denied responsibility for the raid.{{sfn|Walker|1999|p=126}} The escorts then removed the prisoners south to Sutter's Fort and imprisoned by Sutter under Fr\u00e9mont's orders.{{sfnm|Walker|1999|1p=126|Bancroft|1886|2p=123\u201324}} It was at this time Fr\u00e9mont began signing letters as \"Military Commander of U.S. Forces in California\".{{sfn|Walker|1999|p=126}}\n\nOn June 24, Fr\u00e9mont and his men rode to Sonoma arriving on June 25, upon hearing that Californio (people of Spanish or Mexican descent) Juan N. Padilla had captured, tortured, killed, and mutilated the bodies of two Osos, and held prisoner another Osos.{{sfnm|Walker|1999|1p=134|Rogers|1950|2pp=267, 270}} On June 26, Fr\u00e9mont, his own men, Lieutenant Henry Ford and a detachment of Osos, totalling 125 men, rode south to [[San Rafael, California|San Rafael]], searching for Captain Joaquin de la Torre and his Californios Lancers, rumored to have been ordered by Castro to attack Sonoma, but was unable to find them.{{sfn|Walker|1999|pp=134\u201335}} On June 28, Kit Carson and Fr\u00e9mont were near the shores of San Rafael, when three unarmed Californios embarked from a row boat, including [[Jos\u00e9 de los Reyes Berreyesa|Don Jos\u00e9 Berreyesa]] and the Haro twin brothers Ramon and Francisco, sons of [[Francisco de Haro|Don Francisco de Haro]].{{sfn|Solnit|2006}} When Carson asked Fr\u00e9mont what to do with the Californios, Fr\u00e9mont waved his hands and replied, \"I have got no room for prisoners.\"{{sfn|Solnit|2006}} Carson, who was 50 yards away, took his rifle and shot, instantly killing Ramon. His brother Francisco fell on Ramon's body.{{sfn|Solnit|2006}} An order was shouted out, \"Kill the other son of a bitch!\"{{sfn|Solnit|2006}} A shot was fired instantly killing Francisco.{{sfn|Solnit|2006}} When Berreyesa asked why the boys had been shot, he was shot and instantly killed.{{sfn|Solnit|2006}} The bodies were stripped of their clothing and left on the beach.{{sfn|Solnit|2006}} Berreyesa's son Antonio found an American wearing his father's [[serape]].{{sfn|Solnit|2006}} He asked Fr\u00e9mont for the serape to be returned but Fr\u00e9mont refused.{{sfn|Solnit|2006}} Antonio was forced to pay $25 for the garment.{{sfn|Solnit|2006}}{{efn|The incident did not reflect well on Fr\u00e9mont and his men and the killings may have been done in retaliation for the two Osos men who were tortured and killed by the Californios.{{sfn|Rogers|1950|p=270}}}}\n\n[[image:Batalla de Monterey.jpg|thumb|right|Sloat captures Monterey on July 7, 1846. Three days later, Fr\u00e9mont is officially informed the United States was at war with Mexico.]]\nEarly on July 7, 1846, the [[frigate]] [[USS Savannah (1842)|USS ''Savannah'']] and the two [[Sloop-of-war|sloops]], [[USS Cyane (1837)|USS ''Cyane'']] and [[USS Levant (1837)|USS ''Levant'']] of the United States Navy, captured [[Battle of Monterey|Monterey, California]], and raised the flag of the United States.<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/kera/usmexicanwar/biographies/john_sloat.html \"Commodore John Sloat\"]. ''US-Mexican War'', [[Public Broadcasting Service]].</ref>  Commodore [[John D. Sloat]], commanding the U.S. Navy's [[Pacific Squadron]] had his proclamation read in and posted in English and Spanish: \"... henceforth California would be a portion of the United States.\"<ref>Harlow p. 124</ref> On July 10, Fr\u00e9mont learned that the United States was at war with Mexico and he fully cooperated with Commodore Sloat and his senior officer [[Robert F. Stockton]]. Promoted to Commodore and replacing an ailing Sloat, Stockton was put in charge of land operations on July 23, 1846.  Fr\u00e9mont was appointed [[major]] in command of the [[California Battalion]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://catalog.archives.gov/id/140098865 |title=Compiled Military Service Record of Lieutenant Colonel John Charles Fremont, California Battalion Regiment |publisher=National Archives |access-date=August 2, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://catalog.archives.gov/id/118983144 |title=Bounty Land Application File of Lieutenant Colonel John C. Fremont, Colonel Percifer Smith's Regiment of U.S. Mounted Rifles |publisher=National Archives |access-date=August 2, 2019 }}</ref> also called \"U.S. Mounted Rifles\", which he had helped form with his survey crew and volunteers from the [[Bear Flag Republic]], now totaling 428 men.{{sfn|Denton|2011|p=38}}<ref>Bancroft p. 253</ref>{{efn|Unknown to anyone in California until October 1846, Fr\u00e9mont had been commissioned a [[lieutenant colonel]] the previous May by President [[James K. Polk]] while organizing a new regiment of mounted riflemen to fight the newly declared [[Mexican\u2013American War]].<ref>Polk p. 413, Entry for Thursday, 21st May, 1846</ref>}} Stockton incorporated the California Battalion into the U.S. military giving them soldiers pay. Fr\u00e9mont and about 160 of his troops went by ship to San Diego, and with Stockton's marines took Los Angeles on August 13.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} Fr\u00e9mont afterwards went north to recruit more Californians into his battalion.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} In late 1846, under orders from Stockton, Fr\u00e9mont led a military expedition of 300 men to capture [[Santa Barbara, California|Santa Barbara]]. In September, Mexican Californians unwilling to be ruled by the United States, under [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Flores]], fought back and  [[Siege of Los Angeles|retook Los Angeles]], driving out Americans.\n\nIn December 1846, U.S. Brigadier General [[Stephen Watts Kearny|Stephen W. Kearny]] arrived in California having instructions to establish a military control. Kearny, who was undermanned, mistakenly believing war in California had ended, was attacked at the [[Battle of San Pasqual]], but was reinforced when Stockton sent troops to drive off [[Pio Pico]] and the California Lancers.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=21}} It was at this time a dispute began between Stockton and Kearny who had control over the military, but the two managed to work together to [[Battle of Rio San Gabriel|stop the Los Angeles uprising]]. Fr\u00e9mont led his unit over the [[Santa Ynez Mountains]] at [[San Marcos Pass]] in a rainstorm on the night of December 24, 1846. Despite losing many of his horses, mules and cannons, which slid down the muddy slopes during the rainy night, his men regrouped in the foothills (behind what is today Rancho Del Ciervo) the next morning, and captured the [[Presidio of Santa Barbara]] and the town without bloodshed. A few days later, Fr\u00e9mont led his men southeast towards Los Angeles. Fremont accepted Andres Pico's surrender upon signing the [[Treaty of Cahuenga]] on January 13, 1847, which terminated the war in upper California.<ref>Tompkins, Walker A. ''Santa Barbara, Past and Present''. Santa Barbara, CA: Tecolote Books, 1975, pp. 33\u201335.</ref> It was at this time Kearny ordered Fr\u00e9mont to join his military dragoons, but Fr\u00e9mont refused, believing he was under authority of Stockton.\n\n===Court martial and resignation===\n\n[[image: Stephen W. Kearny.jpg|thumb |180px|right |Brigadier General [[Stephen W. Kearny]] humiliated Fr\u00e9mont by having him arrested and court-martialed.]]\nOn January 16, 1847, Commodore Stockton appointed Fr\u00e9mont [[California interim government, 1846\u20131850|military governor of California]] following the [[Treaty of Cahuenga]], and then left Los Angeles.{{sfn|Fr\u00e9mont|1973|p=xxxvii}} Fr\u00e9mont functioned for a few weeks without controversy, but he had little money to administer his duties as governor.{{sfn|Fr\u00e9mont|1973|p=xxxvii}} Previously, unknown to Stockton and Fr\u00e9mont, the Navy Department had sent orders for Sloat and his successors to establish military rule over California.{{sfn|Fr\u00e9mont|1973|p=xxxvii}}<ref>Groom, Winston: Kearny's March: The Epic Creation of the American West, 1846\u20131847 (p. 249)</ref> These orders, however, postdated Kearny's orders to establish military control over California. Kearny did not have the troop strength to enforce those orders, and was forced to rely on Stockton's Marines and Fr\u00e9mont's California Battalion until army reinforcements arrived.{{sfn|Fr\u00e9mont|1973|p=xxxvii}} On February 13, specific orders were sent from Washington through Commanding General Winfield Scott giving Kearny the authority to be military governor of California.{{sfn|Fr\u00e9mont|1973|p=xxxvii}} Kearny, however, did not directly inform Fr\u00e9mont of these orders from Scott.{{sfn|Fr\u00e9mont|1973|p=xxxvii}} Kearny ordered that Fr\u00e9mont's California Battalion be enlisted into the U.S. Army and Fr\u00e9mont bring his battalion archives to Kearny's headquarters in Monterey.{{sfn|Fr\u00e9mont|1973|p=xxxvii}}\n\nFr\u00e9mont delayed obeying these orders, hoping Washington would send instructions for Fr\u00e9mont to be military governor.{{sfn|Fr\u00e9mont|1973|p=xxxvii}} Also, the California Battalion refused to join the U.S. Army.{{sfn|Fr\u00e9mont|1973|p=xxxvii}} Fr\u00e9mont gave orders for the California Battalion not to surrender arms, rode to Monterey to talk to Kearny, and told Kearny he would obey orders.{{sfn|Fr\u00e9mont|1973|p=xxxviii}} Kearny sent Col. Richard B. Mason to Los Angeles, who was to succeed Kearny as military governor of California, to inspect troops and give Fr\u00e9mont further orders.{{sfn|Fr\u00e9mont|1973|p=xxxviii}} Fr\u00e9mont and Mason, however, were at odds with each other and Fr\u00e9mont challenged Mason to a duel.{{sfn|Fr\u00e9mont|1973|p=xxxviii}} After an arrangement to postpone the duel, Kearny rode to Los Angeles and refused Fr\u00e9mont's request to join troops in Mexico.{{sfn|Fr\u00e9mont|1973|p=xxxviii}} Ordered to march with Kearny's army back east, Fr\u00e9mont was arrested on August 22, 1847, when they arrived at [[Fort Leavenworth]]. He was charged with mutiny, disobedience of orders, assumption of powers, and several other military offenses. Ordered by Kearny to report to the [[adjutant general]] in Washington to stand for court-martial, Fr\u00e9mont was found innocent of [[mutiny]], but was convicted on January 31, 1848 of disobedience toward a superior officer and military misconduct.<ref>Groom, Winston: ''Kearny's March: The Epic Creation of the American West, 1846\u20131847'' (p. 259)</ref>\n\nWhile approving the court's decision, President [[James K. Polk]] quickly commuted Fr\u00e9mont's sentence of [[dishonorable discharge]] and reinstated him into the Army, due to his war services. Polk felt that Fr\u00e9mont was guilty of disobeying orders and misconduct, but he did not believe Fr\u00e9mont was guilty of mutiny.{{sfn|Fr\u00e9mont|1973|pp=xlii\u2013xliii}} Additionally, Polk wished to placate [[Thomas Hart Benton (senator)|Thomas Hart Benton]], a powerful Senator and Fr\u00e9mont's father-in-law, who felt that Fr\u00e9mont was innocent. Fr\u00e9mont, only gaining a partial pardon from Polk, resigned his commission in protest and settled in California.<ref>{{cite book |last=Borneman |first=Walter R. |title=Polk: The Man Who Transformed the Presidency and America |location=New York |publisher=Random House Books |year=2008 |pages=284\u201385 |isbn=978-1400065608 }}</ref> Despite the court-martial, Fr\u00e9mont remained popular among the American public.\n\nHistorians are divided in their opinions on this period of Fr\u00e9mont's career. Mary Lee Spence and Donald Jackson, editors of a large collection of letters by Fremont and others dating from this period, concluded that \"...in the California episode, Fr\u00e9mont was as often right as wrong. And even a cursory investigation of the court-martial record produces one undeniable conclusion: neither side in the controversy acquitted itself with distinction.\"{{sfn|Fr\u00e9mont|1973|p=xix}} Allan Nevins states that Kearny:\n: was a stern-tempered soldier who made few friends and many enemies&nbsp;\u2013 who has been justly characterized by the most careful historian of the period, [[Justin Harvey Smith|Justin H. Smith]], as \"grasping, jealous, domineering, and harsh.\" Possessing these traits, feeling his pride stung by his defeat at San Pasqual, and anxious to assert his authority, he was no sooner in Los Angeles than he quarreled bitterly with Stockton; and Fr\u00e9mont was not only at once involved in this quarrel, but inherited the whole burden of it as soon as Stockton left the country.<ref>Nevins 1939b, p. 306.</ref>\n\nTheodore Grivas wrote that \"It does not seem quite clear how Fr\u00e9mont, an army officer, could have imagined that a naval officer [Stockton] could have protected him from a charge of insubordination toward his superior officer [Kearny]\". Grivas goes on to say, however, that \"This conflict between Kearny, Stockton, and Fr\u00e9mont perhaps could have been averted had methods of communication been what they are today.\"<ref>Grivas, pp. 74\u201375</ref>\n\n==Fourth expedition (1848\u20131849)==\nIntent on restoring his honor and explorer reputation after his court martial, in 1848, Fr\u00e9mont and his father-in-law Sen. Benton developed a plan to advance their vision of Manifest Destiny. With a keen interest in the potential of railroads, Sen. Benton had sought support from the Senate for a railroad connecting St. Louis to San Francisco along the 38th parallel, the latitude which both cities approximately share. After Benton failed to secure federal funding, Fr\u00e9mont secured private funding. In October 1848 he embarked with 35 men up the [[Missouri River|Missouri]], [[Kansas River|Kansas]] and [[Arkansas River|Arkansas]] rivers to explore the terrain. The artists and brothers [[Edward Kern]] and Richard Kern, and their brother Benjamin Kern, were part of the expedition, but Fr\u00e9mont was unable to obtain the valued service of Kit Carson as guide as in his previous expeditions.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=PT5IAQAAMAAJ&q=Edward+Kern+1848&dq=Edward+Kern+1848&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDgQ6AEwBWoVChMIzYLMzrKMyAIVytCACh2okA2H  Google Books: \"Edward M. Kern, Artist and Explorer\"], by William Joseph Hefferman; University of California, Berkeley, 1951.</ref>\n\nOn his party's reaching [[Bent's Fort]], he was strongly advised by most of the trappers against continuing the journey. Already a foot of snow was on the ground at Bent's Fort, and the winter in the mountains promised to be especially snowy. Part of Fr\u00e9mont's purpose was to demonstrate that a 38th parallel railroad would be practical year-round. At Bent's Fort, he engaged [[Richens Lacey Wootton|\"Uncle Dick\" Wootton]] as guide, and at what is now [[Pueblo, Colorado]], he hired the eccentric [[Old Bill Williams]] and moved on.\n\nHad Fr\u00e9mont continued up the Arkansas, he might have succeeded. On November 25 at what is now [[Florence, Colorado]], he turned sharply south. By the time his party crossed the [[Sangre de Cristo Range]] via [[Mosca Pass]], they had already experienced days of bitter cold, blinding snow and difficult travel. Some of the party, including the guide Wootton, had already turned back, concluding that further travel would be impossible. Benjamin Kern and [[William S. Williams|\"Old Bill\" Williams]] were killed while retracing the expedition trail to look for gear and survivors.\n\nAlthough the passes through the Sangre de Cristo had proven too steep for a railroad, Fr\u00e9mont pressed on. From this point the party might still have succeeded had they gone up the [[Rio Grande]] to its source, or gone by a more northerly route, but the route they took brought them to the very top of Mesa Mountain.<ref>Both Patricia Richmond in ''Trail to Disaster'' and David Roberts in ''A Newer World'' (New York: [[Simon & Schuster]], 2000) detail the exact route.</ref> By December 12, on Boot Mountain, it took ninety minutes to progress three hundred yards. Mules began dying and by December 20, only 59 animals remained alive.\n\nIt was not until December 22 that Fr\u00e9mont acknowledged that the party needed to regroup and be resupplied. They began to make their way to [[Taos, New Mexico|Taos]] in the [[New Mexico Territory]]. By the time the last surviving member of the expedition made it to Taos on February 12, 1849, 10 of the party had died. Except for the efforts of member Alexis Godey,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anb.org/articles/20/20-01907.html |title=Alexis Godey |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=American National Biography Online |publisher= |accessdate=March 7, 2014}}</ref> another 15 would have been lost.<ref>Roberts, David, ''A Newer World'', p. 241</ref> After recuperating in Taos, Fr\u00e9mont and only a few of the men left for California via an established southern trade route.\n\nEdward and Richard Kern joined J.H. Simpson's military reconnaissance expedition to the Navajos in 1849, and gave the American public some of its earliest authentic graphic images of the people and landscape of Arizona, New Mexico, and southern Colorado; with views of [[Canyon de Chelly]], [[Chaco Canyon]], and [[El Morro National Monument|El Morro (Inscription Rock)]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Canyon De Chelly: Its People and Rock Art|url=https://archive.org/details/canyondechellyit0000gran|url-access=registration|author=Campbell Grant|page=[https://archive.org/details/canyondechellyit0000gran/page/98 98]|year=1978|isbn=978-0816505234}}</ref>\n\nIn 1850, Fr\u00e9mont was awarded the [[Gold Medal (RGS)|Patron's Medal]] by the [[Royal Geographical Society]] for his various exploratory efforts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rgs.org/NR/rdonlyres/C5962519-882A-4C67-803D-0037308C756D/0/GoldMedallists18322011.pdf |title=List of Past Gold Medal Winners |publisher=Royal Geographical Society |accessdate=August 24, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927221002/http://www.rgs.org/NR/rdonlyres/C5962519-882A-4C67-803D-0037308C756D/0/GoldMedallists18322011.pdf |archivedate=September 27, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==''Rancho Las Mariposas''==\n{{further|California Gold Rush}}\n[[image:Trenor William Park.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Trenor W. Park managed Fremont's ''Rancho Las Mariposas''.]]\nOn February 10, 1847, Fr\u00e9mont purchased seventy square miles of land in the Sierra foothills, called ''Las Mariposas'', through land speculator [[Thomas O. Larkin|Thomas Larkin]], for $3,000.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=172}} ''Las Mariposas'' had previously been owned by [[Juan Bautista Alvarado]], former California governor, and his wife Martina Caston de Alvarado.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=172}} Fr\u00e9mont had hoped ''Las Mariposas'' was near San Francisco or Monterey, but was disappointed when he found out it was farther inland by [[Yosemite]], on the [[Miwok]] Indian's hunting and gathering grounds.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=172}} After his court martial in 1848, Fr\u00e9mont moved to ''Las Mariposas'' and became a rancher, borrowing money from his father-in-law Benton and Senator [[John Adams Dix|John Dix]] to construct a house, corral, and barn.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=172}} Fr\u00e9mont ordered a sawmill and had it shipped by the Aspinwall steamer ''Fredonia'' to ''Las Mariposas''.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=172}} Fr\u00e9mont was informed by Sonora Mexicans that gold had been discovered on his property.<ref name=DOAB_p22>[[#DOAB|Dictionary of American Biography]], p. 22</ref> Fr\u00e9mont was instantly a wealthy man, a five-mile quartz vein produced hundreds of pounds of placer gold each month.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=172}}{{efn|His wife, [[Jessie Benton Fr\u00e9mont|Jessie Fr\u00e9mont]], said enormous bags of gold weighing one hundred pounds were produced.<ref name=DOAB_p22/>}} In 1851 [[Hiland Hall]], a former [[Governor of Vermont]], was appointed chairman of the federal commission created to settle Mexican land titles in California;{{sfn|''America's Successful Men of Affairs''|page=494}} he traveled to San Francisco to begin his work, and his son-in-law [[Trenor W. Park]] traveled with him.{{sfn|''America's Successful Men of Affairs''|page=494}}  Fr\u00e9mont hired Park as a managing partner to oversee the day-to-day activities of the estate,{{sfn|''America's Successful Men of Affairs''|page=494}} and Mexican laborers to [[Gold mining#Sluicing|wash out]] the gold on his property in exchange for a percentage of the profits.<ref name=DOAB_p22/> Fr\u00e9mont acquired large landholdings in San Francisco, and while developing his ''Las Mariposas'' gold ranch, he lived a wealthy lifestyle in Monterey.<ref name=DOAB_p22/>\n\nLegal issues, however, soon mounted over property and mineral rights.{{sfn|Richards|2007|pp=172\u201373}} Disputes erupted as squatters moved on Fr\u00e9mont's ''Las Mariposas'' land mining for gold.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=172}} There was question whether the three mining districts on the land were public domain, while the Merced Mining Company was actively mining on Fr\u00e9mont's property.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=172}} Since Alvarado had purchased ''Las Mariposas'' on a \"floating grant\", the property borders were not precisely defined by the Mexican government.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=172}} Alvarado's ownership of the land was legally contested since Alvarado never actually settled on the property as required by Mexican law.{{sfn|Richards|2007|pp=172\u201373}} All of these matters lingered and were argued in court for many years until the Supreme Court finally ruled in Fr\u00e9mont's favor in 1856.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=173}} Although Fr\u00e9mont's legal victory allowed him to keep his wealth, it created lingering animosity among his neighbors.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=173}}\n\n==U.S. Senator from California (1850\u20131851)==\nOn November 13, 1849 General [[Bennet C. Riley]], without Washington approval, called for a state election to ratify the new California State constitution.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=91}} On December 20, the California legislature voted to seat two Senators to represent the state in the Senate.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=93}} The front-runner was Fr\u00e9mont, a [[Free Soil Party|Free Soil Democrat]], known for being a western hero, and regarded by many as an innocent victim of an unjustified court-martial.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=93}} The other candidates were T. Butler King, a Whig, and [[William M. Gwin|William Gwin]], a Democrat.{{sfn|Richards|2007|pp=92\u201393}} Fr\u00e9mont won the first Senate seat, easily having 29 out of 41 votes and Gwin, having Southern backing, was elected to the second Senate seat, having won 24 out of 41 votes.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=93}} By random draw of straws, Gwin won the longer Senate term while Fr\u00e9mont won the shorter Senate term.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=93}} In Washington, Fr\u00e9mont, whose California ranch had been purchased from a Mexican land grantee, supported an unsuccessful law that would have rubber-stamped Mexican land grants, and another law that prevented foreign workers from owning gold claims (Fremont's ranch was in gold country), derisively called \"''Fr\u00e9mont's Gold Bill''\".{{sfn|Richards|2007|pp=115\u201316}} Fr\u00e9mont voted against harsh penalties for those who assisted runaway slaves and he was in favor of abolishing the slave trade in the District of Columbia.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=115}}\n\nDemocratic pro-slavery opponents of Fr\u00e9mont, called the Chivs, strongly opposed Fr\u00e9mont's re-election, and endorsed [[Solomon Heydenfeldt]].{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=115}} Rushing back to California hoping to thwart the Chivs, Fr\u00e9mont started his own election newspaper, the ''San Jose Daily Argus'', however, to no avail, he was unable to get enough votes for re-election to the Senate.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=115}} Neither Heydenfeldt, nor Fr\u00e9mont's other second-time competitor King, were able to obtain a majority of votes, allowing Gwin to be California's lone senator.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=115}} Fr\u00e9mont's term lasted 175 days from September 10, 1850, to March 3, 1851, and he only served 21 working days in Washington in the Senate.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=115}} Pro-slavery [[John B. Weller]], supported by the Chivs, was elected one year later to the empty Senate seat previously held by Fr\u00e9mont.{{sfn|Nevins|1939b|p=396}}\n\n==Fifth expedition (1853\u20131854)==\nIn the fall of 1853, Fr\u00e9mont embarked on another expedition to identify a viable route for a transcontinental railroad along the 38th parallel. The party journeyed between Missouri and San Francisco, California, over a combination of known trails and unexplored terrain. A primary objective was to pass through the Rocky Mountains and Sierra Nevada Mountains during winter to document the amount of snow and the feasibility of winter rail passage along the route. His photographer ([[daguerreotypist]]) was [[Solomon Nunes Carvalho]].\n\nFr\u00e9mont followed the [[Santa Fe Trail]], passing Bent's Fort before heading west and entering the [[San Luis Valley]] of Colorado in December. The party then followed the North Branch of the [[Old Spanish Trail (trade route)|Old Spanish Trail]], crossing the [[Continental Divide]] at [[Cochetopa Pass]] and continuing west into central Utah. But following the trail was made difficult by snow cover. On occasion, they were able to detect evidence of [[John Williams Gunnison|Captain John Gunnison]]'s expedition, which had followed the North Branch just months before.\n\nWeeks of snow and bitter cold took its toll and slowed progress. Nonessential equipment was abandoned and one man died before the struggling party reached the Mormon settlement of [[Parowan, Utah|Parowan]] in southwestern Utah on February 8, 1854. After spending two weeks in Parowan to regain strength, the party continued across the [[Great Basin]] and entered the [[Owens Valley]] near present-day [[Big Pine, California|Big Pine]], California. Fr\u00e9mont then journeyed south and crossed the Sierra Nevada Mountains and entered the [[Kern River]] drainage, which was followed west to the [[San Joaquin Valley]].\n\nFr\u00e9mont arrived in [[San Francisco]] on April 16, 1854. Having completed a winter passage across the mountainous west, Fr\u00e9mont was optimistic that a railroad along the 38th Parallel was viable and that winter travel along the line would be possible through the Rocky Mountains.<ref>{{cite book|editor-last=Spence|editor-first=Mary Lee|title=The Expeditions of John Charles Fr\u00e9mont; Chapter 3; Travels from 1848 to 1854|year=1970|publisher=University of Illinois Press|location=Urbana|url=https://archive.org/details/expeditionsofjoh03fr}}</ref>\n\n==Republican Party presidential candidate (1856)==\n{{further|United States presidential election, 1856|1856 Republican National Convention|Bleeding Kansas|Kansas\u2013Nebraska Act}}\n\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = 399PX-~1.PNG\n| width1 = 100\n| alt1 =\n| caption1 =\n| image2 = Election poster for John C. Fremont (1856).jpg\n| width2 = 190\n| alt2 =\n| caption2 =\n| footer = <center>1856 Republican Party Campaign Posters</center>\n}}\n\nIn 1856, Fr\u00e9mont (age 43) was the first presidential candidate of the new [[History of the Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. The Republicans, whose party had formed in 1854, were united in their opposition to the Pierce Administration and the spread of slavery into the West.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=169}} Initially, Fr\u00e9mont was asked to be the Democratic candidate by former Virginia Governor [[John B. Floyd]] and the powerful Preston family.<ref name=\"DOAB_p22\"/> Fr\u00e9mont announced that he was for Free Soil Kansas and was against the enforcement of the 1850 [[Fugitive Slave Act of 1850|Fugitive Slave Law]].<ref name=DOAB_p22/> Republican leaders [[Nathaniel P. Banks]], [[Henry Wilson]], and [[John Bigelow]] were able to get Fr\u00e9mont to join their political party.<ref name=DOAB_p22/> Seeking a united front and a fresh face for the party, the Republicans nominated Fr\u00e9mont for President over other candidates, and conservative [[William L. Dayton]] of New Jersey, for Vice President, at their June 1856 convention held in Philadelphia.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=170}} The Republican campaign used the slogan \"Free Soil, Free Men, and Fr\u00e9mont\" to crusade for free farms (homesteads) and against the [[Slave Power]].{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=170}} Fr\u00e9mont, popularly known as ''The Pathfinder'', however, had voter appeal and remained the symbol of the Republican Party.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=170}} The Democratic Party nominated [[James Buchanan]].\n\n[[File:John Charles Fremont, engraving.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|right|Image of Fremont taken from 1856 book of Fremont's expeditions]]\n\nFr\u00e9mont's wife Jessie, Bigelow, and Issac Sherman ran Fr\u00e9mont's campaign.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=170}} As the daughter of a Senator, Jessie had been raised in Washington, and she understood politics more than Fr\u00e9mont.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=170}}  Many treated Jessie as an equal political professional, while Fr\u00e9mont was treated as an amateur.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=170}} She received popular attention much more than potential First Ladies, and Republicans celebrated her participation in the campaign calling her ''Our Jessie''.{{sfn|Richards|2007|pp=170\u201371}} Jessie and the Republican propaganda machine ran a strong campaign, but she was unable to get her powerful father, Senator Benton, to support Fr\u00e9mont.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=170}} While praising Fr\u00e9mont, Benton announced his support for Buchanan.<ref>Allan Nevins, ''Ordeal of the Union: A House Dividing, 1852\u20131857'' (1947) pp. 496\u2013502</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n| align = left\n| image1 = RepublicanPresidentialCounty1856.gif\n| width1 = 150\n| alt1 =\n| caption1 =\n| image2 = 1856-Republican-party-Fremont-isms-caricature.jpg\n| width2 = 150\n| alt2 =\n| caption2 =\n| footer = Results by county explicitly indicating the percentage for Fr\u00e9mont in each county. This caricature tries to link Fr\u00e9mont to other \"strange\" movements like [[temperance movement|temperance]], feminists, [[Socialism in the United States|socialism]], [[free love]], [[Roman Catholicism in the United States|Catholicism]] and [[Abolitionism in the United States|abolitionism]].\n}}\n\nFr\u00e9mont, along with the other presidential candidates, did not actively participate in the campaign, and he mostly stayed home at 56 West Street, in New York City.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=170}} This practice was typical in presidential campaigns of the 19th century. To win the Presidency, the Republicans concentrated on four swing states, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Indiana, and Illinois.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=170}} Republican luminaries were sent out decrying the Democratic Party's attachment to slavery and its support of the repeal of the Missouri Compromise.{{sfn|Richards|2007|pp=170\u201371}} The experienced Democrats, knowing the Republican strategy, also targeted these states, running a rough media campaign, while illegally naturalizing thousands of alien immigrants in Pennsylvania.{{sfn|Richards|2007|p=171}} The [[smear campaign|campaign was particularly abusive]], as the Democrats attacked Fr\u00e9mont's illegitimate birth and alleged Fr\u00e9mont was Catholic.<ref name=DOAB_p22/> In a counter-crusade against the Republicans, the Democrats ridiculed Fr\u00e9mont's military record and warned that his victory would bring civil war. Much of the private rhetoric of the campaign focused on unfounded rumors regarding Fr\u00e9mont \u2013 talk of him as president taking charge of a large army that would support slave insurrections, the likelihood of widespread lynchings of slaves, and whispered hope among slaves for freedom and political equality.<ref>Douglas R. Egerton, \"The Slaves\u2019 Election: Fr\u00e9mont, Freedom, and the Slave Conspiracies of 1856.\" ''Civil War History'' 61#1 (2015): 35\u201363.</ref><ref>Allan Nevins, ''Ordeal of the Union: A House Dividing, 1852\u20131857'' (1947) pp. 496\u2013502</ref>\n\nFr\u00e9mont's campaign was headquartered near his home ([[St. George, Staten Island|St. George]]) next to the Clifton ferry landing. Many campaign rallies were held on the lawn, now the corner of Greenfield and Bay Street.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080829062710/http://www.loc.gov/rr/main/republican_conventions.pdf Republican National Political Conventions 1856\u20132008]</ref> Fr\u00e9mont was defeated, having placed second to [[James Buchanan]] in a [[1856 United States presidential election|three-way election]]; he did not carry the state of California. Fr\u00e9mont received 114 electoral votes to 174 votes received by Buchanan. [[Millard Fillmore]] ran as a third party candidate representing the [[Know-Nothing|American Party]]. The popular vote went to Buchanan who received 1,836,072 votes to 1,342,345 votes received by Fr\u00e9mont in November 4, 1856.<ref name=DOAB_p22/> Fremont carried 11 states, and Buchanan carried 19. The Democrats were better organized while the Republicans had to operate on limited funding. After the campaign, Fr\u00e9mont returned to California and devoted himself to his mining business on the Mariposa gold estate, estimated by some to be valued ten million dollars.<ref name=DOAB_p22/> Fr\u00e9mont's title to Mariposa land had been confirmed by the U.S. Supreme Court in 1856.<ref name=DOAB_p22/>\n\n==American Civil War==\n[[File:John C Fr\u00e9mont.png|thumb|upright |Major General John C. Fr\u00e9mont]]\nAt the start of the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], Fr\u00e9mont was touring Europe in an attempt to find financial backers in his California ''Las Mariposas'' estate ranch. President Abraham Lincoln wanted to appoint Fr\u00e9mont as the American minister to France, thereby taking advantage of his French ancestry and the popularity in Europe of his anti-slavery positions. However Secretary of State [[William Henry Seward]] objected to Fr\u00e9mont's radicalism, and the appointment was not made.<ref>Don H. Doyle, ''The Cause of All Nations: An International History of the American Civil War'' (2014) pp. 58\u201359</ref> Instead, Lincoln appointed Fr\u00e9mont [[Union Army]] Major General on May 15, 1861. He arrived in Boston from England on June 27, 1861, and Lincoln promoted him Commander of the [[Department of the West]] on July 1, 1861. The Western department included the area west of the [[Appalachian Mountains]] to the [[Mississippi River]].{{sfn|White|2016|p=156}}{{efn|During his European tour, Fr\u00e9mont had contracted 10,000 rifles from France and $75,000 in cannon and shells from England to be sent to the United States, having obtained the aid of [[Charles Francis Adams Sr.|Charles Francis Adams]], the American minister to Great Britain.{{sfn|Nevins|1939b|p=475}}}} After Fr\u00e9mont arrived in Washington D.C, he conferenced with Lincoln and Commanding General [[Winfield Scott]], himself making a plan to clear all Confederates out of Missouri and to make a general campaign down the Mississippi and advance on Memphis.{{sfn|Nevins|1939b|p=477}} According to Fr\u00e9mont, Lincoln had given him ''[[wikt:carte blanche|carte blanche]]'' authority on how to conduct his campaign and to use his own judgement, while talking on the steps of the White House portico.{{sfn|Nevins|1939b|p=477}} Fr\u00e9mont's main goal as Commander of the Western Armies was to protect [[Cairo, Illinois]] at all costs in order for the Union Army to move southward on the Mississippi River.<ref name=Catton_p27>[[#Catton|Catton]], p. 27</ref> Both Fr\u00e9mont and his subordinate, General [[John Pope (military officer)|John Pope]], believed that [[Ulysses S. Grant]] was the fighting general needed to secure Missouri from the Confederates. Fr\u00e9mont had to contend with a hard-driving Union General [[Nathaniel Lyon]], whose irregular war policy disturbed the complex loyalties of Missouri.<ref name=Catton_p11>[[#Catton|Catton]], p. 11</ref>\n\n===Department of the West (1861)===\n====Command and duties====\nOn July 25, 1861, Fr\u00e9mont arrived in St. Louis and formally took command of a Department of the West that was in crisis.<ref name=Catton_p10/><ref name=Smith_p115>[[#Smith|Smith]], Jean Edward Smith, ''Grant'' (2001)  p. 115</ref> Fr\u00e9mont was forty-eight years old, considered grey haired and handsome.{{sfn|White|2016|p=156}} He brought with him the great reputation as \"the Pathfinder of the West\", for his eleven years of topographical service, and he was focused on driving the Confederate forces from Missouri.<ref name=Catton_p10>[[#Catton|Catton]], p. 10</ref>{{sfn|White|2016|p=156}} Fr\u00e9mont had to organize an army in a slave state that was largely disloyal, having a limited number of Union soldiers, supplies, and arms.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=22}} Guerilla warfare was breaking out and two Confederate armies were planning on capturing [[Springfield, Missouri|Springfield]] and invading Illinois to capture [[Cairo, Illinois|Cairo]].{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=22}} Fr\u00e9mont's duties upon taking command of the Western Department were broad, his resources were limited, and the secession crisis in [[Missouri]] appeared to be uncontrollable.<ref name=Catton_p11/> Fr\u00e9mont was responsible for safeguarding Missouri and all of the Northwest.<ref name=Catton_pp11-12>[[#Catton|Catton]], pp. 11\u201312</ref> Fr\u00e9mont's mission was to organize, equip, and lead the Union Army down the [[Mississippi River]], reopen commerce, and break off the Western part of the Confederacy.<ref name=Catton_p12>[[#Catton|Catton]], p. 12</ref> Fr\u00e9mont was given only 23,000 men, whose volunteer 3-month enlistments were about to expire.<ref name=Catton_p12/> Western Governors sent more troops to Fr\u00e9mont, but he did not have any weapons with which to arm them. There were no uniforms or military equipment either, and the soldiers were subject to food rationing, poor transportation, and lack of pay.<ref name=Catton_p12/> Fremont's intelligence was also faulty, leading him to believe the Missouri state militia and the Confederate forces were twice as numerous as they actually were.<ref name=Catton_p12/>\n\n====Blair feud and corruption charges====\n[[file:General Francis Preston Blair.jpg|thumb|left|Frank Blair was Fr\u00e9mont's political rival in Missouri.]]\nFr\u00e9mont's arrival brought an aristocratic air that raised eyebrows and general disapproval among the people of St. Louis.{{sfn|White|2016|p=156}} Soon after he came into command, Fr\u00e9mont became involved in a [[feud|political feud]] with [[Francis Preston Blair Jr.|Frank Blair]], who was a member of the powerful [[Montgomery Blair|Blair family]] and brother of Lincoln's cabinet member.{{sfn|Oates|1974|p=111}} To gain control of Missouri politics, Blair complained to Washington that Fr\u00e9mont was \"extravagant\" and that his command was brimming with a \"horde of pirates\", who were defrauding the army.{{sfn|Oates|1974|pp=111\u201312}}{{efn|Blair was upset that Fr\u00e9mont had not awarded his friends war contracts.<ref name=Catton_pp_25-26/>}} This caused Lincoln to send Adjutant General [[Lorenzo Thomas]] to check in on Fr\u00e9mont, who reported that Fr\u00e9mont was incompetent and had made questionable army purchases.{{sfn|Oates|1974|p=112}}\nThe imbroglio became a national scandal, and Fr\u00e9mont was unable to keep a handle on supply affairs. A Congressional subcommittee investigation headed by [[Elihu B. Washburne]] and a later Commission on War Claims investigation into the entire Western Department confirmed that many of Blair's charges were true.<ref name=Catton_pp_25-26/>{{sfn|Oates|1974|p=112}}\n\nFr\u00e9mont ran his headquarters in St. Louis \"like a European autocrat\". Perhaps this was due to a sojourn through France before his appointment by President Lincoln. There, Fr\u00e9mont had rented a lavish mansion for $6,000 a year, paid for by the government, and surrounded himself with Hungarian and Italian guards in brassy uniforms.{{sfnm|White|2016|1p=156|Oates|1974|2p=112}} Fr\u00e9mont additionally set up a headquarters bodyguard of 300 Kentucky men, chosen for their uniform physical attributes.<ref name=McFeely_p88>[[#McFeely|McFeely]], p. 88</ref> Fr\u00e9mont had surrounded himself with California associates, who made huge profits by securing army contracts without the competitive bidding required by federal law.<ref name=Catton_pp_25-26/>{{sfn|Oates|1974|p=112}} One Californian contracted for the construction of 38 mortar boats for $8,250 apiece, almost double what they were worth.{{sfn|Oates|1974|p=112}} Another Californian, who was a personal friend of Fr\u00e9mont, but had no construction experience, received a contract worth $191,000 to build a series of forts, which should have cost one third less.{{sfn|Oates|1974|p=112}} Fr\u00e9mont's favorite sellers received \"the most stupendous contracts\" for railroad cars, horses, Army mules, tents, and other equipment, most of them of shoddy quality.{{sfn|Oates|1974|p=112}} A rumor spread in Washington that Fr\u00e9mont was planning to start his own republic or empire in the West.<ref name=Catton_pp30-34>[[#Catton|Catton]], p. 30, 34</ref> Fr\u00e9mont's supply line, headed by Major [[Justus McKinstry]], also came under scrutiny for graft and profiteering.<ref name=Catton_pp_25-26>[[#Catton|Catton]], pp. 25\u201326</ref> Fr\u00e9mont's biographer Nevins stresses that much of Fr\u00e9mont's trouble stemmed from the fact that the newly created Western Department was without organization, war materials, and trained recruits, while waste and corruption were endemic in the War Department under Lincoln's first appointed Secretary, Simon Cameron.{{sfn|Oates|1974|pp=112\u201313}}\n\n====Confederate capture of Springfield====\n[[file:Nathaniel lyon small.jpg|thumb|right|Fr\u00e9mont was blamed for [[Nathaniel Lyon]]'s Union defeat at Wilson's Creek]]\nEarlier in May, a tough, impetuous Regular Army captain, [[Nathaniel Lyon]], exercising irregular authority, led troops who captured a legal contingent of Missouri state militia camped in a Saint Louis suburb; during the capture, civilians were killed.<ref name=Catton_p10/> Missouri had not officially seceded from the Union when Lyon was promoted brigadier general by President [[Abraham Lincoln]] and appointed temporary commander of the Department of the West.<ref name=Catton_p10/> Lyon, who believed a show of force would keep Missouri in the Union, effectively declared war on the secession-minded Missouri governor [[Claiborne Jackson]], who was driven by Lyon to the Ozarks.  Lyon occupied Jefferson City, the state capital, and installed a pro-Union state government.<ref name=Catton_p10/> However, Lyon became trapped at Springfield with only 6,000 men (including Union Colonel Franz Sigel and his German corps).<ref name=Smith_p114>[[#Smith|Smith]], p. 114</ref> A primary concern for Fr\u00e9mont, after he assumed command, was the protection of [[Cairo, Illinois|Cairo]], a Union-occupied city on the [[Mississippi River]], vital to the security of the Union Army's western war effort.  It contained too few troops to defend against a Confederate attack.<ref name=Smith_p115/> Compared to the Confederates, Fr\u00e9mont's forces were dispersed and disorganized.<ref name=Smith_p115/> Fr\u00e9mont ordered Lyon retreat from Springfield and fall back to Rolla, while Fr\u00e9mont personally sent reinforcement troops to Cairo rather than to Lyon, who had requested more troops. Fr\u00e9mont believed with some accuracy that the Confederates were planning to attack Cairo.{{sfn|Nevins|1939b|pp=484, 487}} Lyon, however, hastily chose to attack Confederate General Sterling Price at the [[Battle of Wilson's Creek]], rather than retreat.<ref name=Smith_p115/> During the battle Lyon was shot through the heart and died instantly. As the Union line broke, similar to the first Battle of Bull Run in the east, the Confederates won the battle and captured Springfield opening Western Missouri for Confederate advancement.<ref name=Smith_p116>[[#Smith|Smith]], p. 116</ref> Fr\u00e9mont was severely criticized for the defeat and for Lyon's death, having sent troops to reinforce Cairo, rather than to help Lyon's depleted forces 10 miles south of Springfield.{{sfn|Nevins|1939b|pp=488\u201389}}\n\n====Response to Confederate threat====\n[[File:USGrant01.jpg|thumb |left|[[Ulysses S. Grant]]<br />Fr\u00e9mont put Grant in command of the Union advance to secure the Mississippi River and split the Confederacy in two.]]\nResponding the best he could to the Confederate and state militia threat, Fr\u00e9mont raised volunteer troops, purchased open market weapons and equipment, and sent his wife Jessie to Washington D.C., where she lobbied President [[Abraham Lincoln|Lincoln]] for more reinforcements.<ref name=Smith_p115/> While commanding the Department of the West, Fr\u00e9mont was looking for a brigadier general to command a post at Cairo.<ref name=Catton_p28>[[#Catton|Catton]], p. 28</ref> At first Fr\u00e9mont was going to appoint [[John Pope (military officer)|John Pope]], but upon the recommendation of Major McKinstry, he interviewed unobtrusive Brigadier General [[Ulysses S. Grant]].<ref name=Catton_p29>[[#Catton|Catton]], p. 29</ref> Grant had a reputation for being a \"drifter and a drunkard\" in the Old Army, but Fr\u00e9mont viewed Grant independently using his own judgement.<ref name=Catton_pp28_29>[[#Catton|Catton]], pp. 28, 29</ref> Fr\u00e9mont concluded that Grant was an \"unassuming character not given to self elation, of dogged persistence, of iron will\".<ref name=Catton_p29/> Fr\u00e9mont chose Grant and appointed him commander of the Cairo post in October 1861.<ref name=Catton_p29/> Grant was sent to Ironton, with 3,000 untrained troops, to stop a potential Confederate attack led by Confederate General William J. Hardee.<ref name=Smith_p115/> Immediately thereafter, Fr\u00e9mont sent Grant to Jefferson City, to keep it safe from a potential attack by Confederate General Price a week after the Battle of Wilson's Creek.<ref name=Smith_p16>[[#Smith|Smith]], p. 116</ref>  Grant got the situation in control at Jefferson City, drilling and disciplining troops, increased supply lines, and deploying troops on the outskirts of the city.<ref name=Smith_p16/> The city was kept safe as Price and his troops, badly battered from the Battle of Wilson's Creek, retreated.<ref name=Smith_pp116-117>[[#Smith|Smith]], pp. 116\u201317</ref>\n\nWith Price retreating, Fr\u00e9mont become more aggressive and went on the offensive.<ref name=Smith_p117>[[#Smith|Smith]], p. 117</ref> Fr\u00e9mont knew the key to victory in the West was capturing control of the Mississippi River for the Union forces. Fr\u00e9mont decided to meet Confederate General [[Leonidas Polk]] head-on to control the trunk of the Mississippi.<ref name=Smith_p117/> In a turning point of the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], on August 27, 1861 Fr\u00e9mont gave Ulysses S. Grant field command in charge of a combined Union offensive whose goal was to capture Memphis, Vicksburg, and New Orleans, to keep Missouri and Illinois safe from Confederate attack.<ref name=Smith_p117/> On August 30, Grant assumed charge of the Union Army on the Mississippi.<ref name=Smith_p117-118>[[#Smith|Smith]], pp. 117\u201318</ref> With Fr\u00e9mont's approval, Grant proceeded to capture [[Paducah, Kentucky]], without firing a shot, after Polk had violated Kentucky neutrality and had captured Columbus. The result was that the Kentucky legislature voted to remain in the Union.<ref name=Smith_p119>[[#Smith|Smith]], p. 119</ref>\n\n====Recaptured Springfield====\n[[image:First Battle of Springfield 1861.jpg|right|thumb|First Battle of Springfield]]\nDesiring to regain the upper hand and make up for Union losses at the [[Battle of Wilson's Creek]] and the occupation of [[First Battle of Lexington|Lexington]], Fr\u00e9mont and about 40,000 troops set out to regain Springfield. On October 25, 1861, Fr\u00e9mont's forces, led by Major [[Charles Zagonyi]], won the [[First Battle of Springfield]]. This was the first and only Union victory in the West for the year 1861. On November 1, Fr\u00e9mont ordered Grant to make a demonstration against [[Battle of Belmont|Belmont]], a steamboat landing across the river from Columbus, in an effort to drive Confederate General Price from Missouri.<ref name=Catton_67>[[#Catton|Catton]], p. 67</ref> Grant had early requested to attack Columbus, but Fr\u00e9mont had overruled Grant's initiative.<ref name=Catton_p67-68>[[#Catton|Catton]], pp. 66\u201367</ref>\n\n====Emancipation edict controversy====\n[[file:Abraham Lincoln O-55, 1861-crop.jpg|left|thumb|President [[Abraham Lincoln]] ordered Fr\u00e9mont to rescind his emancipation edict.]]\nFr\u00e9mont came under increasing pressure for decisive action, as Confederates controlled half of Missouri, Confederate troops under Price and McCulloch remained ready to strike, and rebel guerillas were wreaking havoc, cutting railroad cars, telegraph lines, burning bridges, raiding farms, and attacking Union posts.{{sfn|Nevins|1939b|pp=498\u201399}} Confederate sympathies in stronger slave-holding counties needed to be reduced or broken up.{{sfn|Carwardine|2003|pp=177\u201378}} Confederate warfare was causing thousands of Union loyalists to take refuge, penniless, in Illinois, Iowa, and Kansas.{{sfn|Nevins|1939b|p=499}} Radicals in his camp and his wife Jessie urged Fr\u00e9mont to free the slaves of known Confederate supporters.{{sfn|Nevins|1939b|p=499}} They argued that these men were in rebellion and no longer protected by the Constitution, and it was legal to confiscate rebel property, including their slaves.{{sfn|Nevins|1939b|p=499}}\n\nSo, on the morning of August 30, 1861, at dawn, Fr\u00e9mont, without notifying President Lincoln, issued a proclamation putting Missouri under martial law.{{sfnm|Carwardine|2003|1pp=177\u201378|Nevins|1939b|2p=499}} The edict declared that civilians taken in arms against would be subject to court martial and execution, that the property of those who aided secessionists would be confiscated, and that the slaves of all rebels were immediately emancipated.{{sfn|Carwardine|2003|pp=177\u201378}} This last clause caused much concern. Kentucky was still \"neutral\", and Unionists there feared Fr\u00e9mont's action would sway opinion there toward secession. One group in Louisville telegraphed President [[Abraham Lincoln]]:\n\n:\"There is not a day to lose in disavowing emancipation or Kentucky is gone over the mill dam.\"<ref>Guelzo, Allen C. ''Lincoln's Emancipation Proclamation: The End of Slavery in America''. p. 55</ref>\n\nLincoln, fearing that Fr\u00e9mont's emancipation order would tip Missouri (and other Border States) to secession, asked Fr\u00e9mont to revise the order. Fr\u00e9mont refused to do so, and sent his wife to plead his case. President Lincoln told Jessie that Fr\u00e9mont \"should never have dragged the Negro into the war\".{{sfn|Carwardine|2003|p=179}} When Fr\u00e9mont remained obdurate, Lincoln publicly revoked the emancipation clause of the proclamation on 11 September. Fr\u00e9mont's abolitionist allies attacked Lincoln for this, creating more bad feeling.<ref>Guelzo, p. 56</ref> Meanwhile, the War Department compiled a report on Fr\u00e9mont's misconduct as commander in Missouri. This included the arrest of [[Francis Preston Blair Jr.|Frank Blair]], which ended Fr\u00e9mont's alliance with the Blair family, who had backed him for the presidential nomination in 1856.\n\nFinally Lincoln decided Fr\u00e9mont had to go. He issued an order removing Fr\u00e9mont from command of the Western Department, which was hand-delivered to him by Lincoln's friend [[Leonard Swett]] on 2 November. Lincoln's actions prompted much hostility among Radical Republicans throughout the North, even from old friends like Senator [[Orville Browning]]. Lincoln himself later privately stated his sympathy for Fr\u00e9mont, noting that the first reformer in some area often overreaches and fails, but he continued to insist that Fr\u00e9mont had exceeded his authority and endangered the Union cause.<ref>Guelzo, p. 57</ref>\n\n===Mountain departments (1862)===\nAfter being dismissed by Lincoln, Fr\u00e9mont left Springfield and returned to St. Louis.{{sfn|Nevins|1939b|p=550}} On the outside Fr\u00e9mont expressed joy being free from the cares of duty, but on the inside Fr\u00e9mont was smolderingly angry believing the Republicans ran an incompetent war and that the Blairs, acting under malicious motives, were responsible for what he believed to be his unjustified firing by Lincoln.{{sfn|Nevins|1939b|p=550}} More humiliations followed, Fr\u00e9mont's Zagonyi Guard was mustered out of the Army without pay, and all the contracts he made were suspended upon approval from Washington.{{sfn|Nevins|1939b|p=550}} Pressure soon mounted among Radicals and Fr\u00e9mont supporters for his reinstatement of command in the Army.{{sfn|Nevins|1939b|p=550}}\nIn March 1862, Lincoln placed Fr\u00e9mont in command of the Mountain Department, which was responsible for parts of western [[Virginia]], eastern [[Tennessee]] and eastern [[Kentucky]], although he had clearly lost trust in the Pathfinder.{{sfn|Nevins|1939|p=554}}\n\n====Battles of Cross Keys and Port Republic====\n{{see|Jackson's Valley Campaign|Battle of Cross Keys|Battle of Port Republic}}\n[[file:Battle of Cross Keys 1.png|thumb|right|Fr\u00e9mont fought Stonewall Jackson's Army at the '''Battle of Cross Keys'''.]]\nFr\u00e9mont and his army and two other generals, [[Nathaniel P. Banks]] and [[Irvin McDowell]], and their respective armies,  were in charge of protecting the Shenandoah Valley and Washington D.C.{{sfn|Nevins|1939|p=555}} Rather than having these armies under one command, Lincoln and Stanton micromanaged their movements.{{sfn|Nevins|1939|p=555}} Confederate General Stonewall Jackson took advantage of this divided command and systematically attacked each Union Army, putting fear in Washington D.C., taking spoils and thousands of prisoners.{{sfn|Nevins|1939|pp=555\u201356}} Early in June 1862 Fr\u00e9mont pursued the Confederate General [[Stonewall Jackson]] for eight days, finally engaging part of Jackson's force, led by Richard S. Ewell, at [[Battle of Cross Keys]]. Fr\u00e9mont commanded 10,500 Union troops while Ewell commanded about 5,000 Confederate troops.{{sfn|Tucker|2013|p=467}} Fr\u00e9mont had moved down the Valley Pike from the northwest through Harrisonburg to Cross Keys, while Union Brigadier General James Shields closed in from the northeast, hoping to entrap Jackson's forces.{{sfn|Tucker|2013|p=467}} Ewell who was in charge of defending Jackson's western flank established strong defensive positions.{{sfn|Tucker|2013|p=467}}\n\nOn June 8, 1862 at 10:00&nbsp;am Fr\u00e9mont's infantry, composed of German immigrants, advanced on the Confederate line opening the Battle of Cross Keys and slowly pushed back the Confederate advance.{{sfn|Tucker|2013|p=468}} The 15th Alabama Infantry held off Fr\u00e9mont's attack for a half hour, followed by a long range artillery duel. The Confederates, reinforced by the 44th Virginia regiment, beat back several Union assaults.{{sfn|Tucker|2013|p=468}} Fr\u00e9mont launched a major attack, but the Confederates held their fire until the German Union soldiers were up close, releasing a devastating volley that repelled the Union assault.{{sfn|Tucker|2013|p=468}} Fr\u00e9mont withdrew, declining to launch a second assault, and the Confederates gained the territory previously occupied by the Union Army.{{sfn|Tucker|2013|p=468}} Fronting Fr\u00e9mont's Army by a holding brigade, Ewell's men, on order's from Jackson, retreated to Port Republic.{{sfn|Tucker|2013|p=468}} At the Battle of Port Republic the following day, Fr\u00e9mont attacked Jackson's rear flank using artillery, but did not launch a major assault.{{sfn|Tucker|2013|p=1560}} By that afternoon Jackson put his army in motion to Brown's Gap beyond the reach of Fr\u00e9mont's artillery.{{sfn|Tucker|2013|p=1560}} Jackson and his army managed to slip out of the Shenandoah Valley and rejoin Robert E. Lee in Richmond.{{sfn|Tucker|2013|p=1560}} Lincoln ordered Shields and Fr\u00e9mont to withdraw from the Shenandoah Valley.{{sfn|Tucker|2013|p=1560}} Fr\u00e9mont was criticized for being late in linking up with McDowell at Strasburg and allowing Jackson's army to escape.{{sfn|Nevins|1939|p=555}}\n\n===Army of Virginia, New York, and resignation (1862\u20131864)===\n\nWhen the [[Army of Virginia]] was created on June 26, to include General Fr\u00e9mont's corps with [[John Pope (military officer)|John Pope]] in command, Fr\u00e9mont declined to serve on the grounds that he was senior to Pope, and for personal reasons. He went to New York City, where he remained throughout the war, expecting to receive another command, but none was forthcoming.<ref>[http://sunsite.utk.edu/civil-war/ung_f.html U.S. Civil War Generals&nbsp;\u2013 Union Generals&nbsp;\u2013 (Fr\u00e9mont)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070711202327/http://sunsite.utk.edu/civil-war/ung_f.html |date=July 11, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.civilwarstlouis.com/Bios/Fremont.htm|title=John Charles Fremont|publisher=}}</ref> Recognizing that he would not be able to contribute further to the Union Army's efforts, he resigned his commission in June 1864.<ref>{{cite book |last=Egan |first=Ferol |date=1977 |title=Fr\u00e9mont, Explorer for a Restless Nation |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I9ofR29Wd5YC&pg=PA519 |location=Reno, NV |publisher=University of Nevada Press |page=519 |isbn=978-0-87417-096-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Tenney |first=William Jewett |date=1865 |title=The Military and Naval History of the Rebellion in the United States |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rX0FAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA711 |location=New York|publisher=D. Appleton & Company |page=711}}</ref>\n\n===Presidential candidate Radical Democracy Party (1864)===\n{{Further|United States presidential election, 1864#Temporary split in the Republican Party|Radical Democracy Party (United States)}}\nIn 1860 the Republicans nominated [[Abraham Lincoln]] for president, who won the presidency and then ran for re-election in 1864. The [[Radical Republicans]], a group of hard-line [[Abolitionism in the United States|abolitionists]], were upset with Lincoln's positions on the issues of slavery and post-war reconciliation with the southern states. These radicals had bitterly resented Lincoln's dismissal of Fr\u00e9mont in 1861 over his emancipation edict in St. Louis.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=23}} On May 31, 1864, the short-lived ''Radical Democracy Party'' nominated Fr\u00e9mont (age 51) for president in Cleveland.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=23}} Fr\u00e9mont was supported by Radical Republicans, immigrants from Western Germany, and War Democrats.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=23}} This fissure in the Republican Party divided the party into two factions: the anti-Lincoln Radical Republicans, who nominated Fr\u00e9mont, and the pro-Lincoln Republicans.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=23}} On September 22, 1862, Lincoln had issued his own [[Emancipation Proclamation]], effective January 1, 1863, that \"forever\" freed slaves in Southern states fighting under the Confederacy. Fr\u00e9mont reluctantly withdrew from the election on September 22, 1864. The following day, in a prearranged compromise, Lincoln removed ultra-conservative [[Montgomery Blair]] from his cabinet.{{sfn|Nevins|1931|p=23}}\n\n===''Rancho Pocaho''===\nIn 1864, the Fr\u00e9monts purchased an estate ranch in present-day [[Sleepy Hollow, New York]] from the newspaper publisher [[James Watson Webb]]. They named it ''Pocaho'', an Indian name. For Jessie it was a chance to recapture some of the charm and isolation of living in the countryside, now that John had retired from politics.<ref>{{cite book|last=Denton|first=Sally|title=Passion and Principle, John and Jessie Fremont, The Couple whose Power, Politics, and Love Shaped Nineteenth-Century America|year=2007|publisher=Bloomsbury|page=347|isbn=978-1-59691-019-5}}</ref> The house, now at 7 Pokahoe Drive in Sleepy Hollow, is currently a private residence.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lohud.com/story/money/real-estate/homes/sell-this-house/2015/01/16/sleepy-hollow-stone-manor-sale/21770795/ |title=Historic Sleepy Hollow stone manor, $3.4 million |date=January 16, 2015 |newspaper=lohud |publisher=USA Today Network |access-date=August 2, 2019 |first=Bill |last=Cary }}</ref>\n\n==Later life, Arizona territorial governor, and death==\n[[File:Prescott-Sharlot Hall Museum-Fremont House-1875-2.jpg|200px|thumb|John Charles Fr\u00e9mont's Arizona house on display on the grounds of the [[Sharlot Hall Museum]]]]\nThe state of [[Missouri]] took possession of the [[Pacific Railroad]] in February 1866, when the company defaulted in its interest payment. In June 1866 the state conveyed the company to Fr\u00e9mont in a private sale. He reorganized its assets as the [[Southwest Pacific Railroad]] in August, but less than a year later (June 1867), the railroad was repossessed by the state after Fr\u00e9mont was unable to pay the second installment of the purchase price.<ref>{{cite web|year=1960 |url=http://thelibrary.springfield.missouri.org/lochist/frisco/history/100years.cfm |title=100 Years of Service |accessdate=April 20, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828060005/https://thelibrary.springfield.missouri.org/lochist/frisco/history/100years.cfm |archivedate=August 28, 2008 }}</ref> The [[Panic of 1873]], caused by over speculation in the railroad industry, and the depression that followed, wiped out much of Fr\u00e9mont's remaining wealth. Their financial straits required the Fr\u00e9monts to sell Pocaho in 1875, and to move back to New York City.<ref>Denton, p. 354</ref>\n\nFr\u00e9mont was appointed Governor of the [[Arizona Territory]] by President [[Rutherford B. Hayes]] and served from 1878 to 1881. He spent little time in Arizona, and was asked to resume his duties in person or resign; Fr\u00e9mont chose resignation.<ref>{{cite book |title=Rough Rider: Buckey O'Neill of Arizona |last=Walker |first=Dale L. |year=1997 |publisher=University of Nebraska Press |isbn=0-8032-9796-3 |pages=23\u201324 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=bO5HPgpFGbQC |accessdate=August 3, 2010}}</ref> Destitute, the family depended on the publication earnings of his wife Jessie.\n\nFr\u00e9mont lived on [[Staten Island]] in retirement. In April 1890, he was reappointed as a major general and then added to the Army's retired list, an action taken to ease his financial condition by enabling him to qualify for a pension.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Miller |first1=Francis Trevelyan |last2=Lanier |first2=Robert Sampson |date=1911 |title=The Photographic History of the Civil War |volume=10, Armies and Leaders |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CxdHAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA186 |location=New York|publisher=The Review of Reviews Co. |page=186}}</ref>\n\nOn Sunday, July 13, 1890, Fr\u00e9mont (age 77) died of [[peritonitis]] at his residence at 49 West Twenty-fifth Street in New York. His death was unexpected and his brief illness was not generally known. On Tuesday, July 8, Fr\u00e9mont had been affected by the heat of a particularly hot summer day. On Wednesday he came down with a chill and was confined to his bedroom. His symptoms progressed to peritonitis (an abdominal infection) which caused his death.<ref name=opd>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9902E1DD133BE533A25757C1A9619C94619ED7CF \"The Old Pathfinder Dead; Gen. John C. Fremont Expired at his Home Yesterday\"], ''The New York Times'', July 14, 1890</ref> At the time he died, Fr\u00e9mont was popularly known as the \"''Pathfinder of the Rocky Mountains''\".<ref name=opd /> Initially interred at [[Trinity Church Cemetery]], he was reinterred in Rockland Cemetery in [[Sparkill, New York]] on March 17, 1891.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=f000374 |title=Fr\u00e9mont, John Charles, (1813\u20131890) |website=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress |access-date=August 23, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nUpon Fremont's death, his wife Jessie received a Civil War Pension with an annual income of $2,000.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://catalog.archives.gov/id/118983151 |title=Approved Pension File for Jessie Benton Fremont, Widow of Major General John C. Fremont, U.S. Army |publisher=National Archives and Records Administration |access-date=August 1, 2019 |series=Series: Case Files of Approved Pension Applications of Widows and Other Dependents of the Army and Navy Who Served Mainly in the Civil War and the War with Spain, 1861\u20131934 }}</ref>\n\n==Historical reputation==\n[[File:John Charles Fr\u00e9mont.png|thumb|left|John C. Fr\u00e9mont, ''The Pathfinder'']]\nAlthough Fr\u00e9mont was often caught up in controversy, he played a major role in opening up the American West to settlement by American pioneers.{{sfn|McNamara|2016}} His reliable accounts, including published maps, narrations, and scientific documentations of his expeditions, guided American emigrants overland into the West starting in the mid 1840s.{{sfn|McNamara|2016}} Fr\u00e9mont, popularly known as ''The Pathfinder'' during his times, was considered an American hero.{{sfn|McNamara|2016}} Many people believed that Fr\u00e9mont's arrest and court-martial by Kearny during the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] were unjustified.\n\nDuring the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], Fr\u00e9mont's victory over the Confederates at Springfield was the only successful Union battle in the Western Department in 1861. Fr\u00e9mont's reputation, however, was damaged after he was relieved of command by Lincoln for insubordination. After leaving the Mountain Department in 1862, Fr\u00e9mont's active service career in the war virtually ended. Fr\u00e9mont's 1861 promotion of [[Ulysses S. Grant]], going against the grain of Army gossip, was fruitful; Grant went on to become the greatest Union general. He invested heavily in the railroad industry, but the [[Panic of 1873]] wiped out Fr\u00e9mont's fortune, and his appearance thereafter looked tired and aging.\n[[File:NSRW John C Fremont.jpg|thumb|left|John C. Fr\u00e9mont]]\nFr\u00e9mont is remembered for his planting of the American flag on the Rocky Mountains during his first expedition, symbolically claiming the West for the United States. For his botanical records and information collected on his explorations, many plants are named in honor of Fr\u00e9mont. A large statue/sculpture of Fr\u00e9mont is displayed at ''Pathfinder Regional Park'' near Florence, Colorado.<ref>{{cite newspaper |last=Burrous |first=Charlotte |title=Standing TALL: Sculpture of John C. Fremont displayed at Pathfinder Regional Park |newspaper=Canyon City News |url=http://www.canoncitydailyrecord.com/news/canoncity-lolcal-news/ci_24019323/standing-tall-sculpture-john-c-fremont-displayed-at |date=September 4, 2013 |access-date=June 5, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn his memoirs, Fr\u00e9mont coined the phrase \"Golden Gate\" for the strait between Marin County and San Francisco County.\n\nFr\u00e9mont's biographer [[Allan Nevins]] said there were two fascinating things about Fr\u00e9mont.{{sfn|Nevins|1939a|p=1}} The first was the \"unfailing drama of his life; a life wrought out of the fiercest tempests and most radiant bursts of sunshine\".{{sfn|Nevins|1939a|p=1}} The second was Fr\u00e9mont's dramatic career asking, \"How could the man who sometimes succeeded so dazzlingly at other times fail so abysmally?\"{{sfn|Nevins|1939a|p=2}} Nevins said that Fr\u00e9mont's psychological problem was in part attributed to his inheritance of impulsiveness and brilliancy from his \"emotionally and ill-balanced\" parents.{{sfn|Nevins|1939a|p=2}} Nevins said Fr\u00e9mont was encouraged by his parents to heighten his inherited self-reliant, heedless, and adventuresome traits and that he lacked the discipline his passionate spirit and quick mind most needed.{{sfn|Nevins|1939a|p=2}}\n\nConcerning Fr\u00e9mont's tenure as Commander of the West, Lincoln thought Fr\u00e9mont was personally honest, but his \"cardinal mistake\" was that \"he isolates himself, and allows nobody to see him; and by which he does not know what is going on in the very matter he is dealing with.\" Many historians are in agreement with Lincoln.{{sfn|Oates|1974|pp=112\u201313}}\n\nAccording to Rebecca Solnit, in 2006, the celebrated murders of Californios Berryessa and his two nephews on the shores of San Rafael, commanded by Fr\u00e9mont during the [[Bear Flag Revolt]] on June 28, 1846, highlighted a dubious path to California's statehood. {{sfn|Solnit|2006}} Solnit believed that Fr\u00e9mont's unpopularity in California, while Fr\u00e9mont was a Republican candidate during the presidential election of 1856, and losing the state, was in part due to this incident. {{sfn|Solnit|2006}} Although their killings are not disputed, the events surrounding their deaths are in controversy.{{sfn|Heidenreich|2007|p=86}} Fr\u00e9mont and his men may have been taking revenge on the deaths of two Osos by Californios.{{sfn|Heidenreich|2007|p=86}} Fr\u00e9mont may have mistaken the de Haro brothers for soldiers, while others contend that the murders represented the racism of the white Osos. {{sfn|Heidenreich|2007|p=86}} Berryessa and his two nephews may have been considered Indians by [[European Americans]], and received harsher treatment from Fr\u00e9mont and Carson.{{sfn|Heidenreich|2007|p=87}}\n\n==Family==\n[[File:John C. Fremont II (U.S. Navy Admiral).jpg|thumb|John C. Fr\u00e9mont II was a career officer in the United States Navy, and attained the rank of rear admiral.]]\nThe Fr\u00e9monts were the parents of five children:\n* Elizabeth Benton \"Lily\" Fr\u00e9mont, who was born in Washington, DC on November 15, 1842.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.civilwarwomenblog.com/jessie-benton-fremont/ |title=Jessie Benton Fremont: Wife of Union General John C. Fremont |last=MacLean |first=Maggie |date=February 19, 2009 |website=Civil War Women Blog |publisher=Maggie MacLean |ref={{sfnRef|\"Jessie Benton Fremont: Wife of Union General John C. Fremont\"}}}}</ref>  She died in Los Angeles on May 28, 1919.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=May 29, 1919 |title=Daughter of the Pathfinder Dead |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/156012614/ |work=Los Angeles Times |location=Los Angeles |url-access=subscription  |page=1, section II}}</ref>\n* Benton Fr\u00e9mont was born in Washington on July 24, 1848; he died in St. Louis before he was a year old.{{sfn|\"Jessie Benton Fremont: Wife of Union General John C. Fremont\"}}\n* John Charles Fr\u00e9mont Jr., was born in San Francisco on April 19, 1851. He served in the [[United States Navy]] from 1868 to 1911, and attained the rank of rear admiral.  He served as commander of the monitor [[USS Florida (BM-9)|USS ''Florida'']] (1903\u201305), naval attach\u00e9 to [[Paris]] and [[St. Petersburg]] (1906\u201308), commander of the battleship [[USS Mississippi (BB-23)|USS ''Mississippi'']] (1908\u201309) and, finally as commandant of the [[Boston Navy Yard]] (1909\u201311). He died in [[Boston, Massachusetts]] on March 7, 1911.<ref>{{cite news |date=March 8, 1911 |title=Rear Admiral Fremont Dead |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/20622690/ |work=The New York Times |location=New York |url-access=subscription  |page=11}}</ref>\n* Anne Beverly Fremont was born in France on February 1, 1853, and died five months later.{{sfn|\"Jessie Benton Fremont: Wife of Union General John C. Fremont\"}}\n* Francis Preston Fremont was born on May 17, 1855.{{sfn|\"Jessie Benton Fremont: Wife of Union General John C. Fremont\"}} He died in Cuba in September 1931.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 9, 1931 |title=John C. Fremont's Son Dies in Cuba |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/103656931/ |work=Oakland Tribune |location=Oakland, CA |url-access=subscription  |page=8}}</ref>\n\n==Plant eponyms==\n{{See|John C. Fr\u00e9mont botanical nomenclature eponyms}}\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* Western rosinweed ''([[Calycadenia fremontii]])''\n*  pincushion flower ''([[Chaenactis fremontii]])''\n*  goosefoot ''([[Chenopodium fremontii]])''\n*  Fremont's leatherflower ''([[Clematis fremontii]])''\n*  California flannelbush ''([[Fremontodendron californicum]])''\n*  Mexican flannelbush ''([[Fremontodendron mexicanum]])''\n*  silk tassel ''([[Garrya fremontii]])''\n*  moss gentian ''(Gentiana fremontii)''\n* vernal pool goldfields ''([[Lasthenia fremontii]])''\n*  tidytips ''([[Layia fremontii]])''\n*  desert pepperweed ''([[Lepidium fremontii]])''\n*  desert boxthorn ''([[Lycium fremontii]])''\n*  barberry ''([[Mahonia fremontii]])''\n*  bush mallow ''([[Malacothamnus fremontii]])''\n*  monkeyflower ''([[Mimulus fremontii]])''\n*  phacelia ''([[Phacelia fremontii]])''\n*  desert combleaf ''([[Polyctenium fremontii]])''\n*  cottonwood tree ''([[Populus fremontii]])''\n*  desert apricot ''([[Prunus fremontii]])''\n*  indigo bush ''([[Psorothamnus fremontii]])''\n*  mountain ragwort ''([[Senecio fremontii]])''\n*  yellowray gold ''([[Syntrichopappus|Syntrichopappus fremontii]])''\n*  chaparral death camas ''([[Toxicoscordion fremontii]])''\n}}\n\n==Places and organizations named in commemoration==\nFr\u00e9mont is commemorated by many places and other things named in his honor.\n\n===Places===\n[[File:16 21 0060 fremont tree.jpg|thumb|Plaque at [[Henry Cowell Redwoods State Park]], [[Redwood Grove]] trail, where Fr\u00e9mont camped in 1846]]\nUS counties:<ref name=\"Gannett1905\">{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ | title=The Origin of Certain Place Names in the United States | publisher=Govt. Print. Off. | author=Gannett, Henry | year=1905 | page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ/page/n131 132]}}</ref>\n* [[Fremont County, Colorado]]\n* [[Fremont County, Idaho]]\n* [[Fremont County, Iowa]]\n* [[Fremont County, Wyoming]]\n\nCities and towns:\n* [[Fremont, California]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://fremont.gov/149/History | title=History | publisher=City of Fremont | accessdate=January 21, 2018}}</ref> (the largest city that bears his name)\n* [[Fremont, Indiana]]<ref>Taylor, Robert M.; Stevens, Errol Wayne; Ponder, Mary Ann (1990) ''Indiana: A New Historical Guide'', Indiana Historical Society, {{ISBN|978-0-87195-048-2}}, p. 25</ref>\n* [[Fremont, Iowa]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iowaheritage.org/items/show/78615|title=Fremont, IA, 1913; Cedar Township; Mahaska County; Iowa|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Fremont, Michigan]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.epodunk.com/cgi-bin/genInfo.php?locIndex=21803|title= Profile for Fremont, Michigan, MI|publisher= ePodunk|accessdate=August 26, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Fremont, Minnesota]] and [[Fremont Township, Minnesota]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Upham|first=Warren|title=Minnesota Geographic Names: Their Origin and Historic Significance|url=https://archive.org/details/minnesotageogra00uphagoog|year=1920|publisher=Minnesota Historical Society|page=[https://archive.org/details/minnesotageogra00uphagoog/page/n599 582]}}</ref>\n* [[Fremont, Nebraska]]<ref>{{cite book|author=Chicago and North Western Railway Company|title=A History of the Origin of the Place Names Connected with the Chicago & North Western and Chicago, St. Paul, Minneapolis & Omaha Railways|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OspBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA74|year=1908|page=74}}</ref>\n* [[Fremont, New Hampshire]]<ref name=\"Gannett1905\"/>\n* [[Fremont, Steuben County, New York]]<ref name=\"Gannett1905\"/>\n* [[Fremont, Sullivan County, New York]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.fremontny.org/ | title=Town of Fremont | accessdate=January 21, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Fremont, Ohio]]<ref name=\"Gannett1905\"/>\n* [[Fremont, Utah]]<ref name=\"NPSFremont\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nps.gov/media/video/view.htm?id=2777528E-155D-451F-67B33A0D8C954A72 |title=Fremont River |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website= |publisher=U.S. National Park Service |accessdate=September 24, 2014 }}</ref>\n* [[Fremont, Clark County, Wisconsin]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.townoffremont.com/info-fremonthistory.php | title=Area Information \u2013 History of the Town of Fremont | accessdate=January 21, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Fremont, Waupaca County, Wisconsin]] (town){{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n* [[Fremont, Wisconsin]], (village; also in Waupaca County){{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nAlso:\n* [[Fremont, Seattle]], a neighborhood established by migrants from Fremont, Nebraska.<ref name=\"Divjak2006\"/>\n\nGeographical features:\n* [[Fremont Peak (Wyoming)]] in the [[Wind River Mountains]]<ref name=\"Gannett1905\"/>\n* [[Fremont Peak (California)]] in [[San Benito County]], California<ref name=\"Browning2006\">{{cite book|last=Browning|first=Peter|title=Exploring the Back Roads: 28 Day Trips in the Greater Bay Area|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=idt7eUR8G98C&pg=PA116|accessdate=22 January 2018|year=2006|publisher=Great West Books|isbn=978-0944220214|page=116}}</ref>\n* [[Fremont Peak (Arizona)]] in the [[San Francisco Peaks]]<ref name=\"Barnes2016\">{{cite book|last=Barnes|first=Will Croft|title=Arizona Place Names|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CYorDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA170|accessdate=January 23, 2018|date=2016|publisher=University of Arizona Press|isbn=978-0816534951|page=170}}</ref>\n* [[Fremont Pass (Colorado)]], a pass over the [[Continental Divide of the Americas|Continental Divide]] near the headwaters of the [[Arkansas River]]<ref name=\"Gannett1905\"/>\n* [[Fremont Island]] in the Great Salt Lake<ref name=\"Gannett1905\"/>\n* Fremont Canyon on the [[North Platte River]] in Wyoming<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.wyohistory.org/encyclopedia/crossing-wyoming-kit-carson-and-changing-west | title=Crossing Wyoming: Kit Carson and a Changing West | publisher=Wyoming State Historical Society|accessdate=January 23, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Pathfinder Reservoir]] on the North Platte, just upstream from Fremont Canyon<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.wyohistory.org/encyclopedia/pathfinder-dam | title=Pathfinder Dam | publisher=Wyoming State Historical Society|accessdate=January 23, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Fremont River (Utah)]], a tributary of the [[Colorado River]]<ref name=\"NPSFremont\"/>\nOther:\n* [[Fremont\u2013Winema National Forest]] in Oregon<ref>{{cite book | url=https://ir.library.oregonstate.edu/downloads/5999n757t | format=PDF | title=History of the Fremont NAtional Forest | publisher=National Park Service | year=1981| last=Bach | first=Melva M.|accessdate=January 23, 2018}}</ref>\n* The John C. Fremont Trail (the path of Fremont's march into [[Santa Barbara, California]] in December 1846)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ohp.parks.ca.gov/?page_id=21483 | title=San Joaquin | publisher=California Office of Historic Preservation |accessdate=January 23, 2018}}</ref>\n* Fremont Campground in the [[Los Padres National Forest]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dianahembree/2017/06/13/pet-diary-why-dog-friendly-campsites-beat-out-a-four-star-hotel/|title=Pet Diary: Why \"Dog-Friendly\" Campsites Beat Out A Four-Star Hotel|last=Hembree|first=Diana|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-09-13|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Fremont Bridge (Portland, Oregon)]]<ref>Snyder, Eugene E. ''Portland Names and Neighborhoods: Their Historic Origin''. Portland: [[Binford & Mort]], 1979. p. 133.</ref>\n* [[Fremont Bridge (Seattle, Washington)]]<ref name=\"Divjak2006\">{{cite book |title= Seattle's Fremont |author=Divjak, Helen |year=2006 |location=Charleston, SC |publisher= Arcadia Publishing |isbn=978-0738531199 |oclc=70269000}}</ref>\n* [[Fremont Street]] ([[Las Vegas|Las Vegas, Nevada]])<ref>{{cite news | url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2015/nov/15/fremont-school-at-60-years-old-still-performing-it/ | title=Fremont school, at 60 years old, still performing its mission | work=[[Las Vegas Sun]] | first=Brian | last=Greenspun | date=November 15, 2015 |accessdate=January 23, 2018}}</ref>\n* Fremont Ave in Staten Island, NY\n\n===Organizations===\nHospitals:\n* John C. Fremont Hospital, [[Mariposa, California]] (where Fr\u00e9mont and his wife lived during the [[California Gold Rush|Gold Rush]])\n* Fremont Hospital, [[Yuba City, California]]\n\nLibraries:\n* John C. Fremont Branch Library on [[Melrose Avenue]] in Los Angeles.\n* John C. Fremont Library in [[Florence, Colorado]]\n\nSchools and school districts:\n* [[John C. Fremont Senior High School]], Los Angeles\n* John C. Fremont Elementary [[Modesto, California]]\n* [[Fremont High School (Oakland, California)]]\n* [[Fremont High School (Sunnyvale, California)]]; its annual yearbook is ''The Pathfinder''\n* [[Fremont-Elizabeth City High School]], [[Elizabeth, South Australia]] (a [[sister city]] of [[Fremont, California]], which also has a Fremont Park)\n* [[Fremont Unified School District]], [[Fremont, California]]\n* Fremont Junior High School, [[Mesa, Arizona]]\n* Fremont High School, [[Fremont, Nebraska]]\n* Fremont High School, [[Plain City, Utah]]\n* South Fremont High School, [[Saint Anthony, Idaho]]\n* North Fremont High School, [[Ashton, Idaho]]\n* John C. Fremont Middle School, [[Roseburg, Oregon]]\n* John C. Fr\u00e9mont Elementary School, [[Taylorsville, Utah]]\n* Fr\u00e9mont Elementary School, [[Long Beach, California]]\n\n===Other commemorations===\n* The prehistoric [[Fremont culture]], first discovered near the Fremont River\n* The United States honored Fr\u00e9mont in 1898 with a [[commemorative stamp]] as part of the [[Trans-Mississippi Issue]].[[File:Stamp US 1898 5c Trans-Miss.jpg|right|200px|thumb|1898 Fr\u00e9mont commemorative stamp]]\n* The [[Fremont Cannon]], the \"largest and most expensive trophy in college football is a replica of a cannon that accompanied Captain John C. Fr\u00e9mont on his expedition through Oregon, Nevada and California in 1843\u201344\". The annual game between the [[University of Nevada, Reno]] and the [[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]] is for possession of it.<ref>[http://farm1.static.flickr.com/26/47910472_e2b264ee9a.jpg?v=0 Picture of the Fremont Cannon]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.collegefootballhistory.com/nv_wolfpack/history.htm |title=Nevada Wolf Pack History |accessdate=September 19, 2007 |publisher=College Football History }}</ref>\n* The ''Pathfinder Chorus'', a [[barbershop music|barbershop]] chorus in Fremont, Nebraska.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pathfinderchorus.org/ |title=The Pathfinder Chorus |accessdate=February 14, 2014 }}</ref>\n* The Fremont Pathfinders Artillery Battery, an [[American Civil War reenactment]] group from Fremont, Nebraska.<ref>[http://freepages.military.rootsweb.com/~pathfinders/history.htm History of the Pathfinders] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041105030927/http://freepages.military.rootsweb.com/~pathfinders/history.htm |date=November 5, 2004 }} Fremont Pathfinders Artillery Battery. ''URL retrieved on February 19, 2007''</ref>\n* The U.S. Army's (now inactive) [[8th Infantry Division (United States)|8th Infantry Division]] (Mechanized) is called the Pathfinder Division, after Fr\u00e9mont. The gold arrow on the 8th ID crest is called the \"Arrow of General Fr\u00e9mont\". The 8th Division was based at [[Camp Fremont]] in [[Menlo Park, California]] during [[World War I]].\n* In 2000, Fr\u00e9mont was inducted into the [[Hall of Great Westerners]] of the [[National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Hall of Great Westerners |url=https://nationalcowboymuseum.org/hall-of-great-westerners/ |website=National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* In 2013, the [[Georgia Historical Society]] erected a [[historical marker]] at the birthplace of John C. Fr\u00e9mont in [[Savannah, Georgia]].\n\n==Depictions in popular culture==\n===Literature===\n* ''Dream West'' (1983), a biographical novel about Fr\u00e9mont by Western writer David Nevin.<ref>{{cite book |title=Dream West |author=Nevin, David |year=1983 |isbn=0-765-31398-7 |publisher=G.P. Putnam's Sons |location=New York}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/23/books/david-nevin-author-of-historical-novels-dies-at-83.html?_r=0 |title=David Nevin, Author of Historical Novels, Dies at 83 |date=March 22, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |author=Hevesi, Dennis |accessdate=June 2, 2016}}</ref>\n* In the 1992 [[alternate history]] novel ''[[The Guns of the South]]'' by [[Harry Turtledove]], Fr\u00e9mont runs for president in the [[1864 United States presidential election|1864 election]] on a breakaway [[Radical Republican]] ticket with [[Andrew Johnson]] as his running mate. The ticket comes in third place in the popular vote and last in the electoral, getting 10.8% of the popular vote with 436,337 votes and carrying only three electoral votes from [[Kansas]].\n\n===Television===\n* ''[[Death Valley Days]]'', season 15, episode 8, \"Samaritans, Mountain Style\" (1966). Fr\u00e9mont's ([[Richard Simmons (actor)|Dick Simmons]]) scouts Kit Carson and Frenchy Godey encounter a settler in bad trouble.\n* ''[[The Wonderful World of Disney]]'', season 23, episodes 10 and 11, \"Kit Carson and the Mountain Men\" (1977). Fr\u00e9mont [[Robert Reed]] appears as Carson's superior\n* ''[[Dream West]]'',  television [[mini-series]] adaptation of David Nevin's  biographical novel about Fr\u00e9mont ([[Richard Chamberlain]]).\n\n===Film===\n* ''[[Kit Carson (1940 film)|Kit Carson]]'' (1940). Captain Fr\u00e9mont ([[Dana Andrews]]) hires Carson as his scout.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:John Charles Fremont (WMH 04-1858 S 279).jpg\nFile:John C. Fremont, Republican Candidate (4359517745).jpg\nFile:John C. Fr\u00e9mont - Brady-Handy.jpg\nFile:Colonel John C. Fremont on the Rocky Mountains .jpg\nFile:General John C. Fr\u00e9mont, the renowned explorer of the Great Civil War (2).jpg\nFile:Fremont.jpg\nFile:Fr\u00e9mont 1869.jpg\n</gallery>\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:(General John Charles Fremont, Union Army, Republican Candidate for the President of the United States) (6189166341).jpg\nFile:Die Gartenlaube (1856) b 528.jpg\nFile:John C. Fr\u00e9mont 1856.jpg\nFile:1864RadicalPoster.png\nFile:Brooklyn Museum - General John Charles Fr\u00e9mont - Charles Loring Elliott - overall.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Georgia (U.S. state)|California|American Civil War}}\n* [[Fr\u00e9mont Emancipation]]\n* [[List of people pardoned or granted clemency by the president of the United States]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin|35em}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Bancroft|first1=Hubert H. |authorlink=Hubert Howe Bancroft |title=History of California|url=https://archive.org/stream/histofcaliforn05bancroft#page/n11/mode/2up|date=1886|publisher=The History Company|volume=5|location=San Francisco|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Brands |first=H. W. |authorlink=H.W. Brands|title=The Man Who Saved the Union: Ulysses S. Grant in War and Peace |publisher=Doubleday |location=New York |year=2012 |isbn=978-0-385-53241-9 |url=https://archive.org/details/manwhosavedunion0000bran |url-access=registration |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |first=Richard|last=Carwardine|title=Lincol